<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0760 06-25 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0760,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Tribunal Consider's General's Fate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to ADD full quote by Castro. Pickup 5th graf
`The 47-member...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister told a military tribunal
Sunday that a decorated war hero charged with aiding the world's
most notorious cocaine ring gave Cuba a ``stab in the back.''
   Gen. Raul Castro, brother of President Fidel Castro, spoke during
the presentation of charges against Division Gen. Arnaldo Ochoa
Sanchez at the first session of a tribunal of honor hearing the case.
   Ochoa is alleged to have had a three-year involvement with
Colombia's Medellin drug cartel.
   But in his speech, Gen. Castro said Ochoa also was involved in
the smuggling of ivory and diamonds _ a new revelation in the
biggest scandal to rock Cuban power circles in 30 years of communist
rule.
   Ochoa's actions ``represent an outrage, a stab in the back to the
fatherland and a slap in the face,'' he said.
   The 47-member military tribunal of top-ranking officers met
behind closed doors at the Revolutionary Armed Forces headuarters in
downtown Havana all day. The session was to resume Monday.
   A 40-minute videotape of the hearing, including Gen. Castro's
entire speech, took up most of the 8 p.m. news program on state-run
television. A newscaster said eight witnesses, all military
officers, also testified at the hearing.
   Gen. Castro told the court that Ochoa should receive ``punishment
that sets an example'' because he was such a highly regarded officer.
   Authorities say Ochoa was the ringleader of officers who let
cocaine smugglers use Cuban military air bases and arranged for
drug-laden boats to be escorted through Cuba's territorial waters.
   A Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the tribunal will decide if the general is to be stripped of
his rank and ordered to stand trial.
   On June 2, Gen. Castro talked to Ochoa alone about the accusation
he smuggled ivory and diamonds, the defense minister said. He gave
no further details about the accusations.
   ``I hugged him and said that no matter what may happen, today,
tomorrow and always we (the military) would be his brothers,'' Gen.
Castro said.
   It was later, according to informaton that has appeared in the
official newspaper Granma, that Ochoa's connections to drug
trafficking and the Medellin Cartel came to light.
   During Gen. Castro's speech, Ochoa did not once look up and
appeared at times as if he were about to break down. He sat with his
head bowed and a tense look on his face.
   Among the officers on the honor tribunal are four division
generals, 31 brigadier generals, a vice admiral and rear admrial.
   Ochoa, 57, is a veteran of the Cuban revolution who was decorated
for his service as a field commander of Cuban troops in Angola. He
is one of only five officers ever awarded the medal of the Hero of
the Republic of Cuba.
   ``He was admired,'' Lt. Col Fidencio Frias Figueredo, a veteran
of the Angolan conflict, told Radio Rebelde on Sunday in one a
series of interviews on the drug scandal with soldiers and officers.
   ``They should apply the maximum penalty,'' Frias said. ``He has
betrayed the principles of the revolution, he has betrayed the
Revolutionary Armed Forces and, especially, he has betrayed our
maximum leader,'' Fidel Castro.
   Frias, who returned from his second tour of duty in Angola on
June 9, said many of his comrades in arms shared his anger.
``Ochoa's attitude makes our officers indignant,'' he said.
   Along with the indignation came the realization that not even
isolated Cuba is beyond the reach of the Medellin cartel.
   ``The amount of money that they control could turn anybody's
head. These people talk about $4 million like it was nothing,'' said
a Foreign Ministry official who asked not to be named.
   There were reports that U.S. officials wanted to talk to Ochoa.
The ministry official did not rule out the possibility.
   ``These things are from top level to top level,'' the ministry
official said. ``This sort of thing has been done before.''
   He would not elaborate.
   U.S. prosecutors say the names of some of the Cuban officers
surfaced in a 1987 probe of a smuggling ring that culminated in two
indictments and a 1988 trial.
   In addition to Ochoa, Cuban authorities have arrested a brigadier
general, two colonels, a lieutenant colonel, a captain and a major.
   U.S. authorities say an undercover agent flew into Cuba's
Varadero air base in 1987 escorted by Cuban MiGs, and used Cuban
military frequencies.
   Granma, the official newspaper of the Cuban Communist Party, has
said that U.S. allegations about Cuba being a way station for
cocaine traffickers prompted Castro to order the investigation that
led to the arrest of Ochoa and the other officers.
</TEXT>
