<FIRST>r a AM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0729 06-25 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Coast Residents Brace for Possible Storm, Flooding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `At 10:30 ...,' to UPDATE depression's location.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tropical storm watch was posted Sunday along the
northwestern Gulf Coast as the season's second tropical depression,
laden with heavy rain, drifted slowly northward toward Texas.
   ``The surfing and windsurfing are real popular today _ they're
out there right now,'' Corpus Christi police dispatcher Richard Diaz
said. ``Right now it's just raining and the tide is up a little bit,
but another 24 hours and it may be another story.''
   In places along the coast, tides were running 2 to 3 feet above
normal with 6- to 8-foot waves, officials said.
   If the storm strengthened, it could become Tropical Storm Allison.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the depression's poorly defined center was
near latitude 27.5 degrees north, longitude 96.2 degrees west, or
about 70 miles south of Matagorda, Texas, said meteorologists at the
National Hurricane Center in Miami. It appeared to be stalled,
meteorologists said.
   The depression's top sustained wind was estimated at 35 mph, with
higher gusts in heavy rain areas north and east of the center.
   A tropical storm watch was posted for an area stretching from
Baffin Bay, Texas, to Morgan City, La., advising coastal residents
that a tropical storm or incipient tropical storm conditions may
pose a threat. If the sustained wind hits 39 mph, the depression
would become a tropical storm.
   The Galveston County beach patrol banned swimming in the choppy
surf.
   ``It's got the gulf kicked up pretty nasty out there right now,''
beach patrol director Vic Maceo said. ``We're trying to keep all the
inexperienced surfers out of the water.''
   The National Weather Service also extended a coastal flood
warning Sunday for Matagorda and Brazoria counties south of Houston.
   ``We have had some minor flooding in Bay City proper, but it's
only been on a few secondary streets,'' said Craig Sharp, spokesman
for the Matagorda County Sheriff's Department.
   ``The ground is saturated and, of course, if we get a lot more
rain we expect the situation to deteriorate,'' Sharp said.
``Fortunately, so far, the rainfall has been coming in small bands
and the water is still having a chance to run off at this time.''
   The Matagorda area received about 10 inches of rain Saturday,
officials said.
   ``We don't have any reports of flooding yet, but the water's up
high and there's no beach right now,'' said Brazoria County
Sheriff's Department dispatcher Donna Fillmore.
</TEXT>
