<FIRST>r a AM-MayorThreatened 1stLd-Writethru a0606 06-25 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayor Threatened, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0606,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Threatened After Bill Trims Elected Official's Duties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS throughout to clarify; Adds mayor attending Democratic
meeting Saturday, timing of threats, court date for Boykins; no pick up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Vincent C. Schoemehl Jr., who moved his
family to a safe house after allegedly being threatened by the
city's airport commissioner, appeared at a Democratic meeting
Saturday accompanied by police.
   Luther Boykins was arrested late Friday for allegedly threatening
Schoemehl, police said. Police said Boykins was charged with two
misdemeanor counts of third-degree assault that can be based on oral
threats. Boykins allegedly made the threats after the mayor
supported legislation that limited the duties of Boykins' ex-wife,
Billie Boykins, who is the city's license collector.
   ``He specifically said he was going to catch me at my home this
weekend,'' Schoemehl said Saturday. ``I'll just wait until the
police say it's OK to go back.''
   The mayor was escorted by four plainclothes police officers
during an appearance Saturday at an annual meeting of St. Louis
County Democrats in suburban Bridgeton.
   Schoemehl, who launched the effort earlier this year to reduce
Billie Boykins' power, said he moved his family late Friday to the
safe house because of threats Luther Boykins made to two mayoral
aides.
   The alleged threats apparently came shortly before the Board of
Aldermen on Friday voted 16-13 vote to strip Billie Boykins of her
tax-collecting duties. Circuit Attorney George Peach has filed a
lawsuit against her, alleging she lost city money totaling $242,550
in unearned interest and principal because of $2.7 million she
invested in a mutual fund.
   Billie Boykins, 43, a Democrat who was elected in 1982 and
re-elected in 1986, also faces felony drug charges in Bloomington,
Ill., that stem from her arrest near there last fall.
   The board's action Friday reduced Billie Boykins' staff of 54 to
three. It also drastically reduced her $1.1 million budget.
   After it was passed, administrative employees began changing
locks on doors and setting up barricades at the public entrance to
her City Hall office.
   Luther Boykins was released later Friday. He was scheduled to
appear in St. Louis Circuit Court July 6.
</TEXT>
