<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 0127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HeadlineAwards     06-25 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Headline Awards,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Headline Writers Honored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Headline writers gathered Saturday for the
first awards program devoted to honoring their skills.
   The Wuxtry Awards, named for the garbled cry of ``Extra!'' by
newsboys, were created by the International Society for General
Semantics and its journal Et cetera to honor the best _ and worst _
in headlines.
   The Houston Post and the Daily News in New York shared the Wuxtry
prize for best headlines on a given day, while David Sanford, who
edits front-page feature stories for The Wall Street Journal, won
the $1,000 Wuxtry Award for individual achievement in headline
writing.
   ``It's a very interesting, nice job,'' Sanford said. ``Anonymous.
And thankless.''
   One of ten headlines submitted by Sanford topped a story about a
city in Yugoslavia where people wear no clothes: ``Dressing for
dinner remains an issue in the naked city.''
   Finalist Donald Russell of the Philadelphia Daily News wrote his
entry on a story about Prince Charles' horse testing positive for
drugs: ``Just Say Neigh.''
   And David Hall, a finalist from The Orlando Sentinel, submitted
the following on a story describing the difficulty of finding a
taxicab in the Soviet Union: ``Death and Taxis in the U.S.S.R.''
   Russell Joyner, executive director of the semantics society, said
the awards were designed to honor authors of the more than 4 million
headlines that appear annually in the nation's daily newspapers.
   More than 120 entries from U.S. and Canadian dailies in 1988 were
judged by 19 educators, scholars and journalists.
   Commendations also were sent to six finalists in the category of
distinguished individual achievement for their work in 1988.
Recipients were: David Hall, The Orlando Sentinel; Charles
Klaveness, The New York Times; Paul Martin, The Wall Street Journal;
Byron Roberts, The Washington Times; Donald Russell, Philadelphia
Daily News; Steve Steinberg, Dallas Morning News.
   The copy desk crews at the Detroit Free Press, The Washington
Times and the News Journal of Mansfield, Ohio, also received
commendations for best performance by a newspaper's editors.
</TEXT>
