<HEAD>Con Ed Reaches Agreement With One Union, Talks to Continue with Other</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: NEW throughout with Con Ed saying tentative agreement reached
with one union.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Con Edison signed a tentative agreement with a
union representing 600 utility workers early Sunday and agreed at
midnight Saturday to extend a strike deadline by 48 hours with
another union.
   Con Ed spokesman Marty Gitten said the tentative agreement was
reached at about 2 a.m. Sunday with Local 3 of the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
   Talks recessed for the night and were to continue later Sunday
with Local 1-2 of the Utility Workers of America, which represents
14,000 people.
   The utility unions had set a strike deadline of 12:01 a.m.
Sunday. Their three-year contract expired at midnight.
   The unions, which represent clerical and technical workers, have
been seeking improvements in pensions and job safety.
   Gitten said no details would be made public of the tentative
agreement signed by Con Ed and Local 3 pending the union's
notification of its members.
   Earlier, Bea Meltzer, a Con Ed spokeswoman, said that 6,000
management employees would run the utility in the event of a strike,
as they did when the unions last went on strike in 1983 for nine
weeks.
