<FIRST>u a BC-OilSpills 1stLd-Writethru a0639 06-25 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Oil Spills, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0639,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Downgrades R.I. Spill; Tanker in Delaware Spill Floated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th, `The 1.6...', to UPDATE with oil being
blown away from Rhode Island shore. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The oil...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard on Sunday cut its estimate
of an oil spill from the tanker World Prodigy in Rhode Island Sound
by two-thirds.
   Meanwhile, a tanker that spilled an estimated 800,000 gallons in
the Delaware River on Saturday near Wilmington, Del., was floated
early Sunday. Patrols working overnight found beach contamination
from the spill.
   Lt. Alan Brown of the Coast Guard said the Rhode Island spill was
now estimated at 500,000 to 600,000 gallons, far below initial
estimates of up to 1.6 million gallons. The spill occurred Friday
after the tanker hit Brenton Reef at the mouth of Narragansett Bay.
   ``The 1.6 million was the most we could have potentially spilled
if all the oil leaked from all the tanks that were holed,'' Brown
said. ``A good amount of the product that was in those tanks did not
leak out.''
   A helicopter inspection of the area Sunday morning showed less
beach damage than officials had feared. The wind shifted overnight
and most of the oil was being blown out to sea, instead of onto the
state's southwestern beaches, said Gary Ott of the National
Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration.
   The oil remaining in the tanks was being held in place by the
water that rushed in through the holes in the ship's bottom, Brown
said. Crews worked overnight on the delicate task of pumping oil
onto barges.
   The Coast Guard reported early Sunday that a sheen of oil from
the World Prodigy had been seen as far up the bay as East Greenwich,
about 20 miles.
   In the Delaware River spill, Coast Guard patrols worked through
the night and found shoreline contamination _ ranging from heavy to
light _ from Chester, Pa., to New Castle, Del. There is also some
contamination on the New Jersey side.
   In a third oil spill, about 250,000 gallons of heavy crude oil
spilled from a tug-driven barge in a collision with a cargo vessel
Friday night in the Houston Ship Channel at Galveston Bay, Texas.
   Together, the accidents spilled about 1.5 million gallons of oil.
</TEXT>
