<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland     06-25 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Accused of Killing Unarmed Civilian Fined, Back on Duty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young British soldier accused
of killing an unarmed civilian at a border checkpoint has returned
to duty after being fined by the military, the British army said
Sunday.
   Pvt. David Jonathan Holden was 18 when Aiden McAnespie was shot
in the back in February 1988 as he walked past a British army
checkpoint near Aughnacloy, half a mile from the border of Northern
Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.
   McAnespie, 23, was a worker for Sinn Fein, the legal political
wing of the outlawed Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to
drive the British out of the province. The British army said a heavy
machine gun slipped in Holden's wet hands after it had been cleaned
and went off by accident.
   An investigation by the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern
Ireland's police force, concluded one of the three shots fired from
the gun bounced off the road and struck McAnespie in the back.
   But Roman Catholic leaders in the predominantly Protestant
province said McAnespie had been regularly harassed by the army.
   Holden was charged with manslaughter but the charge was dropped
in September for what the prosecuting lawyer said was a lack of
evidence.
   A military inquiry has since decided to fine Holden and return
him to his regiment and full duty, said an army spokesman, speaking
anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   He would not say how large the fine was. He said Holden had been
held in civilian and military custody for six months while the case
was being decided.
   The Irish government launched a separate police investigation
into the shooting, saying a member of the Irish security forces saw
the incident from across the border. The result of the investigation
was never made public.
   Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, the main Roman Catholic party in Northern Ireland, criticized
the way the investigations were handled.
   He said he was surprised ``that the army can find evidence to
discipline him through a fine but that this evidence was not made
available to the director of public prosecutions in relation to the
manslaughter charge.''
   Also Sunday, the outlawed Ulster Freedom Fighters claimed
responsibility for the fatal shooting of a Roman Catholic bartender
in the city of Lisburn.
   The Protestant paramilitary group made its claim in a statement
to Belfast news media.
   Police said at least three men took part in the attack Saturday
on Liam McKee, 36, smashing down the front door of his house with
sledgehammers and shooting him through a bedroom door as he
struggled to keep them out.
   McKee's mother and brother were in the house southwest of Belfast
at the time but were not injured, the Royal Ulster Constabulary said.
   More than 2,700 people have been killed in 20 years of political
and sectarian violence in Northern Ireland.
</TEXT>
