<SECOND>AM-BRF--Berlin Bishop,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Names Bishop To Replace Meisner In Berlin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has named Monsignor Georg
Sterzinsky bishop of Berlin, the Vatican announced.
   The opening was created in December after the pope appointed
Berlin Cardinal Joachim Meisner head of the archdiocese of Cologne,
one of the most influential church posts in Europe.
   Sterzinsky, 54, was vicar general of the apostolic administrator
of Erfurt-Meiningen in East Germany.
   The Vatican said Saturday it complied with a 1929 concordat under
which local clerics help select new bishops. The Berlin clerics
chose Sterzinsky from three candidates nominated by Rome, and the
pope approved their choice.
   Meisner's appointment in December ended a 15-month standoff
between the Vatican and Cologne clerics, who viewed Meisner as too
conservative. A few days before his appointment, the Vatican
declared that the pope had the right to name the Cologne prelate
even if the local church opposed the choice.
</TEXT>
