<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   06-25 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rioters in Soviet Central Asia Storm Police Station, 51 Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of youths armed with sticks, stones and
metal rods stormed a village police station in the Soviet republic
of Kazakhstan, but authorities repelled the attack and arrested 51
people, Pravda said Sunday.
   At least four people have died since ethnic riots broke out June
17 in the oil-producing region of the Central Asian republic.
   Authorities have brought in hundreds of security troops and
declared a curfew to control unrest in the city of Novy Uzen, but
Pravda reported that disturbances have spread to at least five other
municipalities.
   In the town of Mangyshlak, ``a crowd of 150 people armed with
sticks, stones and metal rods attacked a village police station but
was dispersed by helicopters,'' the newspaper said. It did not
elaborate.
   The newspaper quoted Maj. V. Sivushov, an Interior Ministry
spokesman, as saying 51 people were arrested. It said the incident
had occurred in the past 24 hours, but it did not say exactly when.
   A gang of hooligans smashed windows in two trailers housing
workers in the village of Kulsary, then poured gasoline on the
trailers and set them on fire, Pravda said. It did not say whether
anyone was injured.
   The newspaper said ethnic violence had flared in at least five
villages near Novy Uzen, a city of 56,000 people about 800 miles
southeast of Moscow.
   Kazakhstan is the third Soviet Central Asian republic hit by
ethnic violence in the last two months. In the worst rioting, about
100 people died in the Fergana Valley region of Uzbekistan earlier
this month.
   Riots also have been reported in the republic of Tadzhikistan.
   The rioters in Novy Uzen are demanding authorities evict all
members of Caucasus ethnic groups from the city _ more than
one-third of the population. Native Kazakhs complain the Caucasian
settlers dominate oil industry jobs and receive preferential
treatment in housing and other benefits.
   Pravda said 100 ethnic Caucasians were evacuated from the town of
Yeraliev after asking local authorities to guarantee their safety.
   Since the curfew was imposed, the situation in Novy Uzen has
partially stabilized, Pravda said. ``The work of public transit is
being restored. All food shops, canteens and kindergartens are open
and half of the public services are working,'' the newspaper said.
   The town's Communist Party leadership on Saturday fired the Novy
Uzen party chief and replaced him with a prominent local engineer,
Pravda said. It did not elaborate.
   Violence has also been reported recently in the Central Asian
republic of Tadzhikistan, according to reports reaching Moscow over
the weekend.
   The republic's party daily, Kommunist Tadzhikistana, said about
2,000 Meskhi Turks who fled violence in Uzbekistan were attacked on
June 11 in a refugee camp by a mob of 1,000 people demanding they be
moved elsewhere.
   At least two people died and five were wounded when guards
protecting the refugees fired on the gang, the newspaper said.
   Following the attack, authorities began evacuating the Meskhi
Turks by air to central Russia, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890625-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Fish Bjt   06-25 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Fish, Bjt,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Program Battles Afghan Malnutrition With Trout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At dawn each day, two Afghans haul two
bags of hard-boiled eggs, sheep and calves liver nine miles to a
Kabul suburb.
   Basir Amiri and Ismail Kazami are responsible for feeding 80,000
Danish rainbow trout being bred in a swimming pool and eight canals
in a former tourist resort.
   The complex was closed a decade ago when Moslem guerrillas
launched their campaign to overthrow the pro-Soviet government.
   The war not only has left 1.3 million people dead and forced at
least 5 million into exile but also has created food shortages.
Animal breeding has nearly come to a standstill, poultry farms have
closed and fields of many farms have been barren for years.
   The fish-breeding project is one of several projects backed by
the United Nations in Afghanistan. The government took over the
resort and last year turned over parts of it to the Ministry of
Agriculture.
   ``It is a humble effort. We are trying to utilize whatever
facilities we have to provide more protein to the Afghans,'' said
Hari Dewan, chief of the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization,
which oversees the breeding project.
   ``The Afghans are basically red-meat eaters, but we are trying to
tell them to eat fish, if and when available,'' Dewan said.
   In March 1988, the FAO flew 200,000 frozen fish eggs from Denmark
within 36 hours, hatched them in indoor wooden troughs at the resort
and transferred them to the canals that are fed by nearby Kargah
Lake. Eighty thousand have survived.
   ``The trout were doing very well, but soon there was a problem of
space,'' Dewan said. ``We asked the government to give us the unused
swimming pool.''
   There are now about 50,000 trout in the pool.
   The Afghans love meat, and all main dishes are supposed to have a
large portion. Even though meat is available in Kabul, home of 2.25
million people, the price is often too steep for most.
   The government has frozen the price of nan, the flat bread that
is the main staple of the Afghan diet, at about six afghanis, 10
cents at the official exchange rate.
   But the price of mutton has risen about 40 percent this year. A
pound of mutton costs about $6.70. An unskilled laborer in
Afghanistan earns about $60 a month.
   ``Now Afghans hardly get meat to eat. It is very expensive,''
said Syed Ahmed, who runs a downtown restaurant.
   ``I feel bad to ask my brothers (Afghans) for a high price, so I
sell only a very limited amount,'' he said.
   Dewan said 16 tons of rainbow trout will hit the market in a
couple of weeks.
   ``It will be a test case. We will follow up the project depending
on the success and response,'' he said.
   According to a U.N. report on Afghanistan, most Afghans are
malnourished. The average life expectancy is 41 years, and the
infant mortality rate is 200 per 1,000 children.
   ``If the project is successful, it will be good news,'' Dewan
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890625-0023 </DOCNO>
