<FIRST>r i AM-SplittingVenice     06-25 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Splitting Venice,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venice Votes Whether to Split into Two Cities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents voted Sunday on whether they want
to turn Venice into two cities, cutting adrift the soggy section of
town that tourists love but locals are leaving.
   The nonbinding referendum proposes splitting Venice proper _ the
historic and romantic maze of canals and islands _ from Mestre, a
bedroom community across a bridge to the mainland.
   Residents of both communities were voting Sunday and Monday, and
Mestre residents outnumber Venetians 3-1. Results were to be
announced after the completion of voting.
   Ten years ago, a group of influential Venetians lobbied for a
similar referendum. That proposal was defeated, with more than 72
percent of the voters opposed to separation.
   This year's referendum was pressed by Mestre, which has been
steadily absorbing Venice's population. Lacking affordable housing,
young Venetians have been moving to the mainland.
   In 1951, Venice had 175,000 people while Mestre had about 50,000.
In 1987, Venice's population stood at 83,000 while Mestre had
250,000.
   Remaining Venetians, complaining of the scarcity of grocery
stores, go to Mestre to do their shopping. Venice's tourist
development has been virtually unchecked, with shop after shop
converted into sourenir stores.
   Mestre politicians say the growing community's needs are
different from those of aging, tourist-choked Venice and that
Mestre's identity is overwhelmed by Venice's fame.
   Sunday's referendum was consultative only. A vote in favor of
separation would have to be approved by the regional Veneto
government.
   The result will be announced after the completion of voting
Monday afternoon.
   Also voting in a consultative referendum was the seaside city of
Ostia, on whether to split from Rome, 17 miles inland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
