<FIRST>r i AM-Papandreou     06-25 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Papandreou,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Reported Stable After Heart, Kidney Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou, hospitalized
for treatment of pneumonia, was in serious but stable condition on
Sunday after developing heart and kidney complications, officials
said.
   The 70-year-old politician, who underwent open-heart surgery in
September, was admitted to General State Hospital on Thursday with
pneumonia.
   Early Sunday, the hospital said Papandreou had developed heart
and kidney complications, and he was placed on a kidney dialysis
machine. A medical bulletin later said Papandreou's condition was
stable and that he felt better after three hours of treatment with
the machine.
   A team of heart specialists rushed to Athens from London. The
team included Magdi Yacoub, who performed the September heart
surgery. After examining Papandreou, the doctors announced he was
improving and that his heart was ``steady.''
   A son, former Education Minister George Papandreou, told
reporters at the hospital his father ``was in a position to make
decisions and negotiate.''
   The two-term premier, whose socialist party was defeated in
elections June 11, faces a Tuesday deadline to form a new
government. He received the mandate Friday from President Christos
Sartzetakis after conservatives, who finished first in the
balloting, were unable to forge a coalition.
   Papandreou's condition worsened Saturday night and his ex-wife,
Margaret, rushed to the hospital, where she was joined by their four
adult children. Mrs. Papandreou was divorced from her husband this
month.
   Papandreou's 35-year-old girlfriend, Dimitra Liani, also was at
the hospital.
   President Sartzetakis visited Papandreou for 40 minutes on
Saturday and told journalists as he departed that the premier was
alert. An hour later, Sartzetakis left for Madrid to lead a Greek
delegation at a European Economic Community summit.
   Sartzetakis is leading the delegation in Papandreou's stead.
   Throughout the night and early Sunday, hundreds of Papandreou
supporters blocked the entrance to the hospital, shouting slogans
and threatening Papandreou's political opponents as they arrived to
visit. Brief clashes broke out but were quickly stopped by police.
   A hospital announcement said that a team of doctors examined
Papandreou Saturday night and determined that heart and kidney
complications had set in but that he was apparently responding to
treatment for pneumonia.
   Hospital officials said doctors ruled out the possibility of
flying him to London for special treatment because he was too weak
to travel.
   Papandreou is heading a caretaker government, since no party
received a majority in elections to the 300-seat Parliament.
   Papandreou was to confer during the weekend with the leftist
Coalition of the Left and Progress about forming a government with
his socialist Panhellenic Socialist Movement.
   According to constitutional bylaws, Papandreou can be replaced by
the highest-ranking member of his outgoing Cabinet to carry on the
mandate. This would put Anastasios Peponis, former minister to the
premier's office, in charge of negotiations.
   If the socialists fail to form a coalition, it will fall to the
Coalition of the Left and Progress, the third-place finisher, to try
to form a coalition. New elections will be held if that party can't
form a coalition.
</TEXT>
