<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Poll     06-25 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Poll,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Opposition Labor Running 14 Points Ahead of Thatcher's Tories</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Thatcher vs Europe, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition Labor Party jumped to a 14-point
lead over Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's governing Conservative
Party among voters questioned in a public opinion poll published
Sunday.
   The poll in the Observer newspaper follows the trouncing of the
Conservatives by Labor in European Parliament elections. Labor won
its first national election victory since 1974 in the June 15 vote.
   The Observer-Harris poll, conducted Wednesday and Thursday,
showed Labor with the support of 48 percent of those questioned and
the Conservatives with 34 percent.
   The environmental Green Party, which also scored well in the
European Parliament balloting, held the support of 8 percent, while
the centrist Social and Liberal Democrats fell to 6 percent.
   In a poll published the day of the European Parliament elections,
42 percent of those polled backed Labor, 38 percent supported the
Conservatives, 8 percent were for the Democrats and 5 percent for
the Greens.
   The Observer poll also reported 42 percent of those voters
questioned believe that Labor will win the next general election.
   The newspaper did not say how many voters were polled, or give a
margin of error.
   In the European elections, Labor won 45 of the 78 mainland
British constituencies while the Tories won 32, overturning the
45-32 advantage the Tories held in the 1984 Euro-election.
</TEXT>
