<SECOND>AM-Sweden-China,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fang Lizhi Awarded Scandinavian Freedom Prize</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Deng, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major Scandinavian newspapers awarded their
``Freedom Prize'' to Fang Lizhi, the Chinese dissident who has taken
refuge in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, it was announced Sunday.
   The choice ``is a way to express the significance of the present
struggle for democracy in China,'' Sweden's biggest newspaper,
Dagens Nyheter, and the Danish daily Politiken said in a statement.
   Fang, an astrophysicist, has been a ``source of inspiration'' for
the Chinese students' movement for democratic reforms, Dagens
Nyheter said.
   The prize ceremony is scheduled for Sept. 10 in the Danish
capital of Copenhagen.
   ``I'm delighted and will gladly receive the prize if possible,''
Fang told a prize committee official by telephone.
   Fang and his wife, Li Shixuan, escaped to the embassy this month
after the military crackdown on pro-democracy protesters in Beijing.
The Chinese authorities have accused him of ``counterrevolutionary
crimes'' and issued a warrant for his arrest.
   The annual prize, which has a $12,120 award, was founded in 1982.
Earlier winners include Polish Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and
Czechoslovak playwright and dissident Vaclav Havel.
   Fang began criticizing the Chinese society in the early 1950s and
wrote letters to party leaders demanding basic human rights. His
prominent position as a leading scientist at first protected him
from political persecution, but later he was expelled from the
Communist Party.
