<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Robinson 1stLd-Writethru a0662 06-25 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Robinson, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0662,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Anchorman Wanted Death To Help Others, Mother Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore mother's dropped last name.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Max Robinson wanted his death to serve as a
reminder to the black community that AIDS education is important,
the former ABC-TV anchorman's mother said.
   In her first public discussion of the illness that killed
Robinson last December, Doris Robinson Griffin said Saturday that
``people need to be reminded that AIDS victims are human beings.
They are somebody's brother, somebody's father, somebody's sister.
It could happen to anybody, not just homosexuals or drug users.''
   She spoke to a conference on acquired immune deficiency syndrom
held by the Urban League of Hampton Roads.
   Ms. Griffin said Robinson, who was 45 when he died, never told
her how he contracted the human immunodeficiency virus that can lead
to AIDS.
   ``He was very closed-mouthed,'' she said. ``We never talked about
it. We just supported him and loved him.''
   Ms. Griffin said she had rejected several previous invitations to
speak about AIDS ``because the loss was so fresh.''
   ``Only because he wanted his death to be helpful to people did I
decide that I would speak,'' she said.
   Robinson, who began his career at a Portsmouth television
station, became one of the nation's leading black broadcast
journalists, and was named Chicago anchorman for ABC's ``World News
Tonight'' in 1978.
   Ms. Griffin said Robinson tested positive for HIV when he entered
a hospital in 1986 to be treated for alcoholism.
   AIDS is most often transmitted through sexual intercourse, or
sharing of contaminated needles by intravenous drug abusers.
</TEXT>
