<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LastWaltz     06-25 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Last Waltz,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stephen Foster Manuscript For Sale For $225,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A manuscript dealer is advertising for sale a
previously unknown manuscript of a piano waltz written by
19th-century composer Stephen Collins Foster.
   The handwritten music for ``Autumn Waltz'' is signed with
Foster's name and dedicated to ``Miss Thalia Bentel.''
   It is the first fresh composition by Foster to surface in 60
years, according to Dean Root, curator of the Stephen Foster
Memorial at the University of Pittsburgh. And it's the first Foster
manuscript to go on the market in about 30 years.
   Manuscript dealer Rosemary Bufano of Tuckahoe, N.Y., is asking
$225,000 for the manuscript, which she advertised in Sunday's
Pittsburgh Press. The sheet of music was found in a set of books
from the estate of Bentel's heirs. Root verified it last year as
Foster's work.
   Root said ``Autumn Waltz'' is not distinguished and won't rival
the Pittsburgh-born composer's ``Oh Susannah'' and ``My Old Kentucky
Home.''
   ``It's pleasant, simple, a little funny and a little quirky,''
Root said.
   ``It sounds like a song you'd hear at the ice skating rink. Very,
very cute,'' Bufano said. ``It's the kind of sweet little love hymn
you'd expect someone to give a girlfriend in the days before
Hallmark.''
   After Root verified the music for the Rochester, N.Y., antique
book dealer who owned it at the time, the Stephen Foster Memorial
offered to buy the set of books. But its offer was refused, and Root
said he could not increase it because the memorial has no
acquisition fund or endowment.
   Bufano won't say how much she paid for it. She said she decided
to begin her search for a buyer in Pittsburgh because of Foster's
ties to the city.
   Foster is buried in Allegheny Cemetery in the city's
Lawrenceville section. He died in 1864 at age 37 with only 38 cents
in his pockets and no copyright protection or royalty rights for his
heirs.
</TEXT>
