<FIRST>r i AM-BoatPeople     06-25 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat People,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Authorities Arrest Two Men In Killing Of 130 Vietnamese Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai authorities arrested two men
in the killing of 130 Vietnamese boat people in the South China Sea,
refugee officials said Sunday.
   The officials said the Thai suspects were arrested on a fishing
vessel in the southeastern Thai city of Songkhla on Friday and
authorities were looking for another suspect.
   On April 14, 131 refugees left Vietnam in a boat. It was
intercepted two days later by Thai pirates off the Trengganu coast,
about 240 miles northeast of Kuala Lumpur.
   The pirates were armed with shotguns, hammers and knives. They
looted the boat, locked passengers in the hold and cabin, and then
set the boat on fire, officials said.
   The pirates killed several refugees who managed to jump out, but
one 22-year-old man survived and was rescued later by another
Vietnamese refugee boat, they said. The survivor reached Malaysia to
relate the incident.
   No further details were available on the arrests.
   Pirates often plunder vessels that have carried thousands of
Vietnamese from the communist nation.
