<FIRST>r i AM-PapuaNewGuinea     06-25 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Papua New Guinea,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Planning Major Raid on Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIETA, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military forces began preparing
Sunday for a major operation to quell an armed revolt on the
northern island of Bougainville, the armed forces chief said.
   Joint Forces Commander Col. Lima Dotaona said troops would be
deployed to restore order to Bougainville, where rebels have battled
government forces for seven months and forced the closing of a large
copper mine.
   The rebels are led by a 35-year-old surveyor, Francis Ona, who
vowed last year to close the Bougainville Copper mine and demanded a
referendum on seccession and nearly $10 billion in compensation for
environmental damage allegedly caused by the mine.
   ``If he decides to come out we are prepared to let him, but it
has to be on our terms,'' said Dotaona of Ona. ``Our aim is simple _
we are going to restore law and order.''
   He said troops would begin moving into the bush Monday morning to
begin what was expected to be a protracted operation against the
rebels.
   ``It's a dangerous operation and you can expect casualties,'' he
said. ``Once the security forces are in there ... if there is armed
resistance they will respond in an appropriate manner.''
   In an address to the nation on radio and television Friday, Prime
Minister Rabbie Namaliu said the government could not allow a
``criminal minority'' to threaten the unity and economic stability
of the nation.
   Ona and his Bougainville Republican Army closed the mine May 15
and have since defied all attempts at conciliation, repeatedly
ambushing mine workers and soldiers sent to restore order.
   Prior to its closing, the mine contributed 20 percent of Papua
New Guinea's total revenue.
   Three soldiers have died and about 20 other members of the
security forces and numerous civilians have been wounded in the
unrest.
   Tensions have been high on Bougainville because local landowners
objected to profits being made from the island's copper mine, which
ranks among the world's 10 biggest open-cut copper mines.
   Australia's biggest mining company, CRA Ltd., jointly operates
the mine, which is about 300 miles northeast of the mainland.
   Papua New Guinea, with a 3.5 million mainly Melanesian
population, is just north of Australia. It gained independence from
Australia in 1975.
</TEXT>
