<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Election     06-25 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Election,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Held In Bangladesh Region Torn By Insurgency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHAGRACHARI, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its first attempt at
grass-roots democracy, Bangladesh held district council elections
Sunday in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, a remote region of primeval
forests and straw huts where a bush war has simmered and
periodically flared for 14 years.
   The candidates, the voters and the soldiers who patrol the area
concede the elections probably will not end the insurgency by
Buddhist tribal rebels who seek to expel Bengali Moslem settlers who
arrived in the past decade.
   The rebels _ who belong to the Shanti Bahini, or peace force _
tried to frighten their fellow tribesmen away from the polls with
death threats and by burning at least a score of villages in the
last two months.
   There were no reports Sunday of any killings on election day, but
the government said at least 12 potential voters were killed in the
past two months and thousands more had fled to neighboring India or
into nearby jungles.
   More than 4,000 people have died since the insurrection started
in 1974 in this region of 5,200 square miles that starts 130 miles
southeast of Dhaka and stretches along the borders with India and
Burma.
   Election results, which were not expected before Monday, are
largely immaterial, since the ethnic makeup of the three district
councils was predetermined by the government and weighted with a
two-thirds majority favoring the tribes over the settlers.
   For instance, Bengalis ran against fellow Bengalis, Chakma
tribespeople ran against Chakmas, Tripura tribespeople ran against
Tripuras.
   The elections were conducted on a non-party basis, and a dozen
candidates who talked with reporters were unable to enunciate any
platform other than they would work on a ``democratic'' basis to
decide local affairs, such as controlling new settlements, levying
local taxes and hiring local police.
   The Chakmas, Tripuras and at least 11 other tribes made up more
than 90 percent of the Chittagong Hills' population 40 years ago.
Diluted by an influx of Bengali settlers in the past decade, they
now comprise only 60 percent by government estimates.
   Many voters had no idea how to mark their ballots, strips of
paper printed with symbols such as fish, deer, teakettles and
bicycles to represent each of the 240 candidates running for the
three 31-member district councils.
   But just about everyone except the Shanti Bahini seemed to agree
the elections were a step in the right direction in this nation,
which has never changed presidents via the ballot box since its
war-won independence in 1971.
   Bangladesh, formerly east Pakistan, has had nine presidents since
the break with west Pakistan. Each one was installed through
military intervention, usually a coup or assassination.
   The incumbent, Hussain Muhammad Ershad, achieved power through a
bloodless coup in 1982. Four years later he was declared the winner
of an election that his opponents and foreign observers said was
clearly fraudulent.
   Ershad, who has governed Bangladesh longer than anyone else, has
shown increasing sensitivity to international opinion, especially
since a devastating cycle of cyclones, floods and droughts prompts
him to seek millions of dollars in foreign aid each year for this
overpopulated nation of 110 milion people.
   With an annual per capita income of $160, Bangladesh is one of
the world's poorest countries.
   Although the national Parliament is elected by ballot, major
opposition parties usualy boycott the elections because they refuse
to recognize Ershad. District councils have always been appointed by
the government in the past.
   ``There is no alternative to the elections,'' said Samiran Dewan
Chakma, 33, who runs a construction company in Khagrachari and was
elected unopposed to be chairman of the Khagrachari District
Council. ``After the election we will have political and cultural
guarantees for the life of our people.''
   Like many hills residents, he uses the name of his tribe as a
surname.
   Although he and several military officials predicted high voter
turnouts, there were signs the guerrillas' threats had taken a toll.
   In the hamlet of Baradum, all 10 houses stood deserted even
though they were barely 30 yards from an army camp set up to provide
protection. Lt. Col. Mohammad Sadiq Rumi said the families living in
the houses fled a month ago after tribal rebels told them not to
vote.
   In Naniarchar, about 30 miles southeast of Khagrachari, hundreds
of Chakma voters fled in panic when about 25 rifle shots were heard
a couple of miles away.
</TEXT>
