<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     06-25 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Najib Taps Old Foe for Top Government Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib appointed the brother
of the man he ousted as president to serve as first deputy prime
minister, officials said Sunday.
   Mahmoud Baryalai, 45, is the brother of former President Babrak
Karmal, whom Najib ousted two years ago. Diplomatic sources,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the appointment of Baryalai
indicated Najib was consolidating his power.
   ``Our doors are open to anyone who wants to join the national
reconciliation plan,'' Foreign Minstry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani
told reporters.
   Najib has offered the U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas a role in the
government, but the rebels have rejected the overtures and vow to
topple his Marxist regime.
   In another development, the government said Sunday it instructed
its mission in New Delhi to issue a visa to a U.S. diplomat to
negotiate the release of American photographer Tony O'Brien.
   O'Brien was arrested by Afghan troops on June 14 in Wardak
province while he was traveling with Moslem rebels.
   The United States closed its embassy in Kabul weeks before Soviet
troops completed their withdrawal from Afghanistan in February.
Washington and Kabul have no formal diplomatic ties and the United
States is one of the main suppliers of the rebels.
   ``I would like to assure the family members of Mr. O'Brien and
the American people that he is in good health in Kabul,'' Amani told
reporters.
   He said the United States requested the visa.
   The government accused O'Brien, who was on assignment for
Time-Life Inc., of being in the country without a visa and in the
company of armed guerrillas.
   The appointment of Baryalai makes him the No. 2 official behind
Prime Minister Ali Kishtmand in the 27-member Council of Ministers.
   Baryalai was a member of the ruling People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan but was disgraced, imprisoned and kept under house
arrest in Kabul after his brother was ousted in December 1986.
   ``To establish peace in Afghanistan, our door is open to all who
want to join us,'' Amani said.
   Diplomatic sources said the inclusion of Baryalai is broadening
Najib's support. ``At least what it seems to be on the surface is
that he is further consolidating his position,'' said one Asian
diplomat.
</TEXT>
