<FIRST>r w AM-Mitchell-Iran-Contra     06-25 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mitchell-Iran-Contra,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Majority Leader Sees No Need To Reopen Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Intelligence Committee's report on
why some White House documents on the Iran-Contra affair were not
turned over to Congress does not warrant a reopening of the overall
inquiry, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said Sunday.
   ``There is no basis at this time, in my judgment, for a
resumption of the investigation or for the creation of a new
investigation,'' Mitchell said.
   The Maine Democrat had asked the Senate panel to examine why
congressional investigators never saw the six previously undisclosed
White House memos when copies surfaced during the trial of former
national security aide Oliver North.
   In a 51-page report Friday, the intelligence panel said the White
House sometimes handled documents in chaotic and haphazard manner
when Congress sought them for its Iran-Contra hearings two years
ago. But the committee said there was no evidence of a calculated
cover-up by the Reagan administration.
   Among those documents was a Feb. 19, 1985 memo to former
President Reagan from then-National Security Adviser Robert
McFarlane.
   The memo recommended that Reagan write Honduran President Roberto
Suazo to reaffirm U.S. support for Contra rebels in Nicaragua and
pledge U.S. help in defending Honduras if Nicaraguan troops crossed
its border.
   Located in an informal ``heads of state'' file in a box of papers
at Reagan's presidential library in California, the document
suggested a ``quid pro quo'' arrangement with Honduras that has been
denied by President Bush. At the time, Congress had banned direct
U.S. aid to the Contras.
   ``Obviously, there are loose ends,'' Mitchell said Sunday in an
interview on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
   ``Not every single question has been answered and every one may
not be answered,'' said Mitchell, who served on the special
Iran-Contra investigating committee. ``But there comes a question of
balance in terms of whether one should or should not reopen the
investigation.''
   Mitchell said more about Reagan's role in the funneling of
proceeds from arms sales to Iran to the Contras will likely surface
during the upcoming trials of John Poindexter, who succeeded
McFarlane as national security adviser, and former Air Force Gen.
Richard Secord.
</TEXT>
