<FIRST>r a AM-NukeTest     06-25 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuke Test,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Erratic Winds Again Force Postponement of Nuclear Weapon Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERCURY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major underground nuclear weapon test was
postponed for a second day Sunday because of erratic winds at the
Nevada Test Site.
   The test, code named Amarillo, had been scheduled for Saturday
morning, then postponed until noon after a series of delays caused
by shifting winds.
   ``We had the same problem as Saturday, an erratic wind pattern,''
Energy Department spokesman Jim Boyer said Sunday afternoon.
Scientists want to conduct the test in calm or steady winds so that
if any radioactive gas accidentally escaped from the site it could
easily be tracked.
   Boyer said a weather briefing will be held Monday afternoon and
the test would not be conducted before Tuesday at the earliest.
   Officials planned to detonate a nuclear device packing an
explosive punch equivalent to up to 150,000 tons of TNT at the site
105 miles northwest of Las Vegas. A similar test took place Thursday
without incident.
   Both weapons were classified as having a range of between 20 and
150 kilotons, the upper limit allowed under existing treaties with
the Soviet Union.
   The weekend blast was to be the seventh announced test of the
year at the site where the nation's nuclear weapons are detonated
underground.
</TEXT>
