<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-25 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boaters who worry their pooches will tire of
the dogpaddle in the event of an accident can keep them afloat with
specially designed life jackets _ one of many pet products being
hawked at an exposition here.
   ``So many people like to take their dogs with them on their
boats. And a lot of people have swimming pools,'' said Tom Boog of
Black Sheep, the Texas company which makes Puppy Preservers.
   Black Sheep is among 230 companies displaying their wares at the
American Pet Products Manufacturers Association meeting this weekend
at the Rivergate convention center.
   The industry association estimates that Americans spend nearly $4
billion a year on pet food, toys, cleanup gear and even clothing,
and about the same amount on veterinary care.
   For people who prefer fish to Fido, the convention featured
displays of designer aquariums, such as a headboard with a 25-gallon
fish tank or a coffee table aquarium.
   Also on display: pet videos; a flea trap that uses a light bulb
to attract fleas and sticky paper to hold them; sweaters, pillows
and beds emblazoned with National Football League team logos; live
crickets to feed to small reptiles, frogs, fish, birds and even
tarantulas; and Dogloo, a plastic igloo dog house.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ARCADIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature doesn't know it yet, but
Louisiana now has an official state possum song, courtesy of the
Arcadia Possum Festival.
   Seven people entered Saturday's possum sing-off _ the main event
of the seventh annual celebration of a slow, ugly animal that never
got its fair share of fur.
   The winner was Bobbie Jean Ellis, who bested entries such as
``Glory, Glory, Possum-luia'' and ``Possum Rock'' with her gospel
ballad, ``You've Got a Friend in a Possum.''
   It celebrates the opossum as the critter is most often seen:
   ``Poor fast fuzzy, he got killed.
   ``They tell me he died with a Goodyear tattoo
   ``Now how would you like for that to have been you?''
   Wayne Dring, a newspaper editor, and some of his drinking buddies
in this north Louisiana town dreamed up the festival while swapping
stories about road kills and other cultural relics.
   They formed Possums Unlimited _ a take-off on the hunters'
conservation group called Ducks Unlimited _ and organized the
festival.
   It hasn't gotten real big yet, but it has left its mark on the
town that previously has been known only as the spot where federal
agents killed outlaws Bonnie Parker and Clyde Barrow in 1934.
   To echo a tombstone-style marker on the outskirts of town where
Bonnie and Clyde were ambushed, a gravestone was erected in the
center of town sporting the inscription, ``In memory of all departed
possums.''
   Many attractions at the possum festival are more-or-less standard
fare: arm wrestling, a domino tournament, a golden girls pageant, a
weed arrangement contest featuring roadside wildflowers.
   But the main event is always something different, and this year
it was the song contest. Last year, townsfolk competed in a possum
funeral preach-off. The year before, a man was tried for
intentionally hitting an opossum with his car.
   ``We wrote a story that said the man intentionally ran over a
marsupial. Local folks read that and didn't know what he did,'' said
Dring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
