<DOCNO> AP890625-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     06-25 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary's Party Reformers Determined To Push Through Democratic Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist reformers, apparently
strengthened after a crisis meeting of the policy-setting Central
Committee, seem determined to push through democratic policies to
bolster the party in next year's elections.
   On Sunday, the state-run MTI news agency reported that one of the
most influential of dozens of independent political groups, the
Hungarian Democratic Forum, proclaimed itself a political party.
   The promotion on Saturday of economic reformer Rezsoe Nyers to
communist party chairman and the formation of a four-man presidium
dominated by advocates of democratic change indicated the growing
strength of party reformers.
   Nyers, Minister of State Imre Pozsgay and premier Miklos Nemeth,
all well-known reformers, will now run the party along with general
secretary Karoly Grosz. The power of Grosz, party chief for 13
months, has been severely curbed.
   The four will lead the party on a provisional basis until a
crucial party Congress set for Oct. 7, when communists will choose
who will lead the party as Hungary prepares for its first free and
competitive elections next year.
   ``It was a maintaining operation, ensuring the party to hold on
and preventing it from falling apart before the Oct. 7 Congress,'' a
Western diplomat said.
   The choice of a leader at the Congress is considered crucial to
the party's attempts to hold power when the elections are held.
   The independent daily Mai Nap on Sunday quoted an unidentified
party official as saying: ``This was a conscious compromise in which
everybody knew the rules of the game. Previously, compromises were
made in secret ... but at the Congress we'll speak openly.''
   Increasingly open conflicts between reformers and conservatives
left Grosz little middle ground. Several party reform groups called
for his ouster ahead of the two-day Central Committee meeting.
   His inclusion in the new leadership suggested the reformers, who
are popular in the country at large, had been forced to strike a
balance with disgruntled conservatives who are still powerful in the
party.
   The first act of the new leadership was to revamp the nine-man
party Politburo, expanding its membership to 21 and renaming it the
Political Management Committee.
   The new Politburo contained all nine members of the old body but
added reformers such as Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, influential
historian Maria Ormos and Csongrad county party boss Pal Vastagh.
   The reformers believe that only their more democratic policies
can give the party hope of emerging as the strongest force from next
year's elections and then forming a coalition government with the
strongest of some 30 democratic opposition groups.
   A public opinion poll last month conducted by two leading
sociologists showed that only 36.5 percent of those queried would
vote for the Hungarian Socialist Workers' (communist) Party if free
elections were be held within one month.
   According to the survey, the ruling communists, together with the
social democrats, would muster just about 50 percent, enough to form
a leftist coalition Cabinet.
   Others support the independent groups such as the Hungarian
Democratic Forum.
   Earlier this month, Zoltan Biro, a member of the 15-man
presidium, told a conference the Forum would call for elections, now
expected in June 1990, to be moved up.
   It has become ``increasingly clear'' that the communists are
unable to lead Hungary out of its current economic and social crisis
alone, MTI quoted him as saying.
</TEXT>
