<HEAD>Oil Spills At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spills Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some facts and figures on the status
Sunday of the multiple marine oil spills around the nation Friday
and Saturday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>RHODE ISLAND:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek tanker World Prodigy struck a reef Friday at mouth of
Narragansett Bay not far off Newport, R.I. Spill of heating oil
estimated Sunday at 600,000 gallons, down from earlier estimates of
up to 1.6 million gallons. Some shoreline was fouled but north wind
Sunday pushed most oil out to sea and some beaches reopened.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DELAWARE:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Uruguayan tanker Presidente Rivera ran aground early Saturday in
Delaware River near Claymont, Del., spilling about 800,000 gallons
of industrial heating oil. Some oil fouled shore on both Delaware
and New Jersey sides of river, plus some upstream in Pennsylvania.
Tanker was refloated Sunday and taken to a refinery dock to be
unloaded.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TEXAS:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A tug-driven barge ruptured when it collided Friday with a cargo
ship in the Houston Ship Channel near La Porte, Texas. Channel
connects Galveston Bay and Houston. Spill of heavy crude oil
estimated at 250,000 gallons. Most of the oil that washed ashore
affected industrial property.
</TEXT>
