<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     06-25 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alfred Jarry's `Ubu' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yesterday's shouting can become today's snores.
   A case in point is the Lincoln Center Theater's production of
``Ubu,'' an adaptation of Alfred Jarry's ``Ubu Roi,'' which opened
Sunday at the Mitzi Newhouse Theater.
   The play with its scatalogical language, incessant cruelty,
smutty jokes and haphazard dramatic structure caused a major dust-up
when it was first presented in Paris in 1896. A shocked bourgeois
fled, but the avant-garde embraced it. Through the years, the play
has been championed by such diverse theater people as Peter Brook
and Lynne Meadow and such cultural institutions as the Living
Theater and the San Francisco Mime Troupe.
   But the new Lincoln Center production won't win ``Ubu'' many new
fans. Theatergoers at a recent preview performance appeared more
bored than scandalized. Most of them gamely waited out director
Larry Sloan's 85-minute production, which at least has a sense of
style if not substance.
   Although it's still possible to shock an audience today, ``Ubu''
doesn't. It seems almost quaint _ and inevitable _ in its defiance
of authority. The story is cartoonish, even childish, but then the
play was written when Jarry was a teen-ager. It concerns Pere Ubu,
an egotistical tyrant who murders the king of Poland and then takes
over the country, slaughtering its noblemen, lawmakers and
businessmen in his quest for more power.
   Ubu is sort of a dung-heap Macbeth but without the wisdom
Shakespeare's king gains from his downfall. Jarry's title character
flees at the end of the play, learning nothing from his excesses.
Neither does the audience, but that may be Jarry's point.
   Sloan, who adapted the play with Doug Wright, has added the
character of Ubu's Conscience, present in another Jarry play about
Ubu, to this production. But it's a voice the king repeatedly
ignores and finally silences forever.
   Ubu's wife resembles a dance hall floozy, while a dozen or so
other actors play an assortment of kings, queens, nobles, lawyers,
soldiers and even a bear.
   It's hard to judge the acting in such a comic-strip atmosphere,
but Oliver Platt is terrific in the title role. He looks like Porky
Pig's evil twin, a porcine bully harassing the weak but running away
from the strong. He makes sympathy for the character out of the
question, something Jarry probably would agree with completely.
   Jodie Markell is equally unpleasant as Ubu's wife and Barnabas
Miller is dead on target as the whining nerd of a prince who
challenges Ubu.
   In one novel bit of casting, playwright and sometime-actor
Christopher Durang, author of ``Sister Mary Ignatius ...,'' plays
Ubu's Conscience, but the only person Durang appears to be
impersonating is himself.
   The set by Douglas Stein is a huge white-tiled room with a
walkway above the thrust stage and a bright red backdrop to comment
on the bloody action.
   Lincoln Center should be applauded for attempting ``Ubu,'' a work
rarely seen in mainstream theater. They have given it the best
possible production, but the play doesn't support their efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890625-0049 </DOCNO>
