<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Executions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>14 Drug Traffickers Hanged; 50,000 Addicts To Be Sent To Labor Camps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with 50,000 alleged drug traffickers
to be sent to labor camps. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen drug traffickers were hanged in
northeastern Iran Sunday and 50,000 addicts will be sent to
hard-labor camps, Iranian news reports said.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
said 40,000 other addicts will be cared for by the prisons welfare
system.
   Tehran radio, also monitored in Cyprus, said the 14 convicts were
hanged in prison in the northeastern city of Mashhad in Khorasan
province. Some were accused of smuggling arms and committing
``unvirtuous acts,'' a euphemism for prostitution.
   Sunday's hangings brought to 757 the number of drug-related
executions reported since December, when Parliament passed a law
mandating death for possession of even small quantities of narcotics.
   There are an estimated 2 million addicts and pushers in Iran.
   The human rights group Amnesty International has said the law is
to cover up the execution of political prisoners.
</TEXT>
