<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0678 06-25 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Kill One Palestinian Attacker; Two Collaborators Slain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with body of second collaborator
found, more Arabs injured, Rabin meeting with justice minister; Pickup
7th pvs, ``An Israeli...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked Palestinians wielding hatchets and knives
ambushed an Israeli patrol in the Gaza Strip on Sunday and the
troops opened fire, killing one attacker.
   Also Sunday, the bodies of two Palestians suspected of
collaborating with Israeli authorities were found. Other clashes in
the occupied lands left seventeen Palestinians wounded and an
Israeli soldier injured, reports said. The army confirmed eight
wounded.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin met with justice minister Dan
Meridor on Sunday to discuss expansion of legal measures the army
can employ in the occupied territories, Israel television said.
   Rabin seeks to extend the current six-month norm of detention
without trial and wants to simplify procedures leading to
deportation of Palestinian activists, Israeli news reports said.
   In the West Bank town of Nablus, the body of 21-year-old Nidal
Salhab was found Sunday, his head smashed with a heavy object, the
army and Palestinian reporters said.
   An Arab reporter said Salhab was killed because he was suspected
of collaborating with Israeli authorities. He said masked men led
Salhab out of his house Friday as he was shouting: ``I will return
(to my people), I will stop collaborating.''
   The army said the case was under investigation.
   The body of another Arab was found in Qatana near Jerusalem, the
army said, and Israel television reported the man was suspected of
collaborating with the Israelis. He was not identified.
   At least 67 alleged collaborators are among the 535 Palestinian
victims of the 18-month anti-Israeli uprising. Twenty-three Israelis
have also died.
   An Israeli soldier was injured in the head by a rock in the West
Bank city of Hebron and troops then forced merchants on the street
to shut their shops, Arab reports said.
   In the Gaza city of Khan Yunis, soldiers on patrol were attacked
by masked assailants with hatchets and knives, an army spokesman
said. The spokesman said the troops opened fire, killing 28-year-old
Youssuf Abdel Karim Farara.
   Arab reports said two other Palestinian attackers were wounded.
   Two assailants were captured, the army spokesman said.
   In Jerusalem, an Israeli judge ordered seven Jewish settlers held
an additional three days on suspicion of involvement in the shooting
death of a Palestinian youth during a hike near the West Bank
village of Bani Zeit.
   Also Sunday, police ordered ballistic tests of Uzi submachine
guns held by Jewish settlers in the Hebron area as part of an
investigation into the shooting death of a Palestinian in March, the
radio said.
   Meanwhile, an official of the Save the Children Federation denied
reports that one of the group's workers, Chris George, was refusing
to cooperate with Israeli authorities investigating his kidnapping
last week.
   Israel's displeasure with George, 35, co-director of the
federation in the occupied territories, stems from his refusal to
give the army an account of his 30-hour captivity in the Gaza Strip,
three Israeli newspapers said.
   The Maariv daily said George, who was abducted Thursday and
released the following day, may be asked to leave for allegedly
helping his abductors compose a letter demanding freedom for seven
jailed Palestinian activists.
   A military analyst for the Yediot Ahronot daily said officials
understood George may have written the letter under duress.
   Neal Keny, regional director for Save the Children, said in a
telephone interview that George was debriefed three times by
soldiers since his captivity and in the presence of U.S. Embassy
officials.
   ``These allegations are outrageous and without basis. Chris is
completely cooperating with the investigation,'' Keny said. George
was away for the weekend and could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
