<HEAD>Syrians Shell Christian Ports; Sunni Moslem Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf `There were...' with 1 graf to ADD dropped word
``no'' to show no immediate reports of injuries. Pickup 5th graf `The Syrians...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners shelled Christian ports
north of the city Sunday to maintain their blockade, and police said
a kidnapped Sunni Moslem civil servant was released after four days
in captivity.
   The gunners, deployed in the Moslem sector of the Lebanese
capital, shelled the ports of Jounieh and Byblos with rounds of
Soviet-designed 130mm mortars. The ports have become the Christians'
only link with the outside world.
   Aoun's gunners opened up with 155mm howitzers on the seaside
boulevard of west Beirut where several Syrian batteries are
entrenched.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries.
   The Syrians have harassed the besieged Christian enclave since
the latest round in the 14-year-old civil war began March 8.
   Fighting between Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's
20,000 soldiers and the 40,000-strong Syrian troops began when Aoun
blockaded illegal militia-run ports because he said they cost his
government $100 million yearly in lost revenues.
   Syrian troops, in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate, responded by shelling the 310-square-mile Christian enclave.
   By police count, 373 people have been killed and 1,460 wounded in
the 14 weeks of fighting. Several Arab league calls for a
comprehensive cease-fire have been undermined.
   U.S. Secretary of State James Baker has reiterated a U.S. call
for the Lebanese to show restraint to avert further bloodshed,
Moslem officials said Sunday.
   Baker reportedly made his appeal in a letter sent to acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem Cabinet vying for power
with a rival Christian government, officials at Hoss' office said.
   The existence of the letter could not be confirmed Sunday and it
was not known whether Baker sent a similar document to Aoun.
   Police said the abducted civil servant, Raja Bsat, who works at
the Ministry of Economy, was freed late Saturday. They did not
identify his abductors or give other details.
   A previously unknown group, calling itself Father of the Poor,
took responsibility for Bsat's abduction in Syrian-policed west
Beirut on Wednesday to protest a bread shortage.
   The latest fighting has led to power rationing and shortages of
food, fuel and hospital supplies on both sides of divided Beirut.
   Also Sunday, pro-Iranian Shiite fundamentalists protested Saudi
Arabia's restrictions on the number of Moslems allowed to visit the
holy shrines of Mecca and Medina during the annual pilgrimage season.
   In Moslem west Beirut, about 100 members of Hezbollah, or Party
of God, staged a demonstration outside Hoss' home, shouting ``death
to (King) Fahd'' of Saudi Arabia.
   The Saudi government last year introduced a quota of 1,000
pilgrims for every 1 million people from each Islamic nation until
it can expand facilities in the holy cities.
   Some 2 million Moslems usually converge on Mecca and Medina
during the pilgrimage, which Moslems are required to make at least
once. The pilgrimage season climaxes in mid-July.
</TEXT>
