<FIRST>r a AM-Swastika-Stabbing     06-25 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swastika-Stabbing,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivor Of Auschwitz Slain Over Swastika</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 72-year-old survivor of a Nazi death camp was
bludgeoned and stabbed to death in a boarding house by a man he'd
accused of scrawling a swastika on his door, police said.
   ``The guy might have stabbed him, but the war still killed him,''
said the victim's son, Lenny Kowalski, 38. ``It was the insignia
that did it.''
   Max Kowalski's body was found Saturday in the room of Ruben
Martinez Zucarino, 36, who was charged with second-degree murder,
said police Sgt. Maurice Howard.
   The victim, known to his friends as ``The Mayor of Brighton
Beach,'' lived with his wife in Manhattan, but spent his days in a
rented room at the Brooklyn boarding house fixing old televisions
and radios as a hobby.
   The younger Kowalski said he was visiting with his father in the
workshop Saturday morning when he noticed the swastika and a skull
and crossbones scrawled in blue felt-tip pen on the door.
   ``I said, `Who do you think could have done it?''' said the son.
``He said he'd had some words with the guy next door over him not
cleaning up the kitchen earlier this week.''
   Max Kowalski then quietly washed the marks from the door, said
his son.
   The younger Kowalski complained to the landlady, Tuey Chin, who
said that when she asked Zucarino about the graffiti he was holding
a marker of the same blue color in his hands. But he told her he
knew nothing about the drawings.
   A short time later, Max Kowalski went to Zucarino's apartment,
where he confronted him about the swastika, police said.
   A fight ensued. Zucarino stabbed Kowalski repeatedly with a
scissors and a fork and smashed a religious statue over his head,
killing him, police said.
   Kowalski, a Polish Jew whose family died at the Auschwitz
concentration camp, came to the United States in 1949 and worked as
a carpenter. He and his wife, also a Holocaust survivor, raised two
sons.
</TEXT>
