<FIRST>r i AM-Nepal-India     06-25 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nepal-India,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Delays Nepal-Bound Fuel at Border Amid Trade, Transit Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRGUNJ, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian checkpoint near this border city
on Sunday blocked 110 tanker trucks carrying fuel to Nepal, hit by
acute shortages caused by a three-month-old trade and transit
dispute between two countries.
   The 3,300-gallon tankers carrying gasoline, kereosene and diesel
oil from Singapore were lined up at the checkpoint at Raxaul in the
eastern Indian state of Bihar.
   Shyam Bihar Rai, the driver of one Indian-registered tanker
truck, said the convoy's documents were cleared by Calcutta port
customs in eastern India, ``yet these people (Indian customs
officials) at Raxaul are not allowing us to cross the border to
enter Nepal.''
   Indian customs officials say each truck would be allowed to carry
only 10.6 gallons of fuel in its own fuel tank to reach its
destination in Nepal. One official said this was a precaution
against possible smuggling.
   But the drivers said they needed more than that in their fuel
tanks to make the return journey to Calcutta.
   India and Nepal have been embroiled in a dispute since March 23,
when their trade and transit treaties expired. The Indian government
has closed 13 of the 15 trade points along its 1,000-mile border
with landlocked Nepal.
   One of those still open is Raxaul, connected by a small wooden
bridge with Birgunj, 75 miles south of Katmandu.
   A senior Nepalese officer said the Indian move to stop the
imports from Singapore was intended to further pressure his country.
   ``It was a surprising move. They even stopped releasing the cargo
imported by Nepal from a third country,'' Zonal (administrative)
Commissioner Tek Bahadur Thapa told reporters. ``It seems the action
has been taken to create more hardships for the Nepalese.''
   India traditionally has been a supplier of petroleum products to
Nepal, but after the trade and transit agreements expired, the
Indian oil corporation stopped handling petroleum products for Nepal.
   The resulting shortages have led to fuel rationing in Nepal. A
car owner is allowed to buy only 2.6 gallons a week.
   Nepal has imported some petroleum products through neighboring
Tibet and airlifted some from Bangladesh.
</TEXT>
