<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov     06-25 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway Visit Better Late Than Never, Nobel Winner Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei D. Sakharov came to Norway Sunday, 14
years after the Soviet human rights activist won the Nobel Peace
Prize but was not allowed to travel there to accept it.
   ``Better late than never,'' said Sakharov, who is on a tour of
Western Europe. ``I should have been here in 1975, but I was delayed
by a few years.''
   Soviet authorities denied him permission in 1975 to travel to
Oslo to receive that year's Nobel Peace Prize from the Norwegian
Nobel Committee. His wife, Yelena Bonner, accepted it on his behalf.
   Sakharov, 68, spoke briefly with reporters upon arrival at an
Oslo airport from London. He and his wife were invited to Norway by
the Nobel Committee and other organizations.
   ``It's a very happy moment for us,'' said Jakop Sverdrup, the
Norwegian Nobel Committee's permanent secretary. ``He is 14 years
too late but we are glad he finally made it.''
   During Sakharov's six-day visit he is scheduled to meet with
Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland, Foreign Minister Thorvald
Stoltenberg and Soviet Embassy officials.
   The nuclear physicist, who helped develop Soviet nuclear weapons,
also will visit research institutes in Oslo and the Michelsen
Institute for Science and Intellectual Freedom in Bergen.
   ``My wife was Norway's guest a few years ago and what she told me
of the visit made me anxious to visit,'' said Sakharov, speaking
Russian to a Norwegian interpreter.
   The couple made an earlier stop in the Netherlands. They leave
Norway for Switzerland on July 1.
   Sakharov was elected to the newly formed Congress of the People's
Deputies by the Soviet Academy of Sciences in April, three years
after he was freed from internal exile in the city of Gorky. He had
been sent there as punishment for his dissident activities,
including criticism of the 10-year Soviet military intervention in
Afghanistan that began in 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
