<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     06-25 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Prevent Anti-government Rally and Detain 16; Steep Tobacco
Price Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 16 people Sunday and
prevented a banned independence group from rallying to protest the
expected presidential candidacy of Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, an opposition spokesman said.
   Also Sunday, authorities announced consumers were to pay an
average of 83 percent more for tobacco products beginning Monday,
the state-run news agency PAP reported. Price hikes in the past have
sparked labor unrest.
   Police drove a car through the crowd gathered in Lublin, 100
miles southeast of Warsaw, to force protesters to disperse. They
arrested members of the Confederation for an Independent Poland,
including its leader Leszek Moczulski, said Zygmunt Lenyk, the
group's spokesman.
   Protesters shouted ``Jaruzelski must go,'' as they marched to the
downtown Communist Party headquarters, where they burned a copy of a
local party newspaper that supported the Polish leader's candidacy.
   The presidency was created under an accord reached between the
government and opposition in April. The accord led to partially free
elections earlier this month and to legalization of the trade union
after a seven-year ban.
   Solidarity won 99 of 100 seats in the newly created Senate and
161 seats _ all the places open to the opposition _ in the lower
house.
   The National Assembly will meet in early July to elect the new
president who in turn will choose a new prime minister. Because the
Communist Party and its allies have a majority, the presidency was
widely expected to go to Jaruzelski.
   Though he helped broker the democratic reforms, Poles are wary of
Jaruzelski, who imposed martial law in Dec. 1981 to crush
Solidarity. During the martial law thousands of opposition activists
were imprisoned or lost their jobs.
   The confederation vowed to hold rallies nationwide to oppose
Jaruzelski's nomination.
   Solidarity-supported lawmakers postponed making a decision at
their first meeting Friday.
   Citing increased production costs, the state-run tobacco company
Interbac raised the price for a package of its cheapest Polish
cigarettes from the equivalent of 10 cents to 19 cents.
   In the week since Poland held the second round of elections,
authorities have raised prices of sugar, gasoline, alcohol and items
such as refrigerators and washing machines by 40 to 70 percent.
   Inflation this year is officially projected at 60 percent but
unofficially is running at more than 100 percent.
   In a statement, a union umbrella group warned that ``the latest
price rises and rumors of others soon threaten an outburst of public
anger,'' the Polish news agency, PAP reported Sunday.
</TEXT>
