<FIRST>r i AM-ThatchervsEurope 2ndLd-Writethru a0670 06-25 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher vs Europe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0670,0863</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher vs. Europe Again, But She's Looking Weaker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9 `But Mrs...single currency.' with 6 grafs to
UPDATE with comments Sunday night. Pickup 10th graf `In a signal...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the 12-nation European Economic
Community meet Monday for an epic battle with familiar lineups:
Margaret Thatcher vs. the rest of Europe.
   But at this two-day summit the British prime minister for the
first time confronts her allies looking like something of a loser _
trounced in this month's European Parliament elections and presiding
in Britain over 8.3 percent annual inflation and 14 percent interest
rates.
   In London, a poll published Sunday in the Observer newspaper
indicated her Conservatives trail the opposition Labor Party by 14
points. It said 42 percent of those polled believe Labor will win
the next general election.
   Critics, including some within her own Conservative Party, think
Mrs. Thatcher is cornered.
   They argue that if she continues blocking EEC proposals for a
single European currency and a ``social charter'' on workers' rights
and welfare, Britain will find itself sidelined.
   ``There is nothing whatever the United Kingdom can do to stop
this,'' said Lord Cockfield, whom Mrs. Thatcher removed last year as
one of Britain's two representatives at EEC headquarters in
Brussels, Belgium.
   ``All it can do is to leave itself sitting lamentably by the
wayside .... We need to take a more honest and humbler view of our
circumstances. Perhaps, after all, we need Europe more than Europe
needs us,'' he said in a speech last week.
   Mrs. Thatcher believes the social charter smacks of socialism and
the monetary union infringes on British sovereignty. She shows no
sign of changing her mind at the Madrid summit.
   Mrs. Thatcher met Sunday evening with Dutch Prime Minister Ruud
Lubbers, a possible ally in the monetary dispute. A British official
said later, ``They have a lot of common ground. ... Both sides want
a pragmatic approach to the issue and to get an agreed resolution''
at the summit.
   But he said Mrs. Thatcher remained adamant that Britain would not
be pulled into any process that would lead inevitably to a single
central bank and one currency for the 12 nations. The official spoke
with the condition of anonymity.
   West German government spokesman Hans Klein saw some hope. He
said Sunday it appeared British officials ``are not being as
hard-line as they were before.'' Lutz Stavenhagen, a senior aide to
West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, said ``I see possibilities that
we'll come to a common position.''
   Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez said he will press the
other leaders to make sweeping changes in monetary policies that
would lead to a single currency and central bank.
   ``We're not trying to exclude anyone,'' Gonzalez said in an
interview published in Madrid's El Pais newspaper. ``But neither
should anyone have the right to hold back the desire of those who
want to advance toward a monetary union. This message should be
understood.''
   In a signal last week that they will force Mrs. Thatcher's hand,
foreign ministers Roland Dumas of France and Hans-Dietrich Genscher
of West Germany declared they want ``a decisive political impulse to
be given in Madrid in favor of economic union.''
   On the social charter, Genscher said the EEC must go further than
the single market of 320 million people to be created when trade
barriers are dismantled in 1992.
   ``Workers in the 12 states must feel at home in this Europe,'' he
said.
   The EEC proposals encapsulate what Mrs. Thatcher dismisses as
grandiose and impractical moves toward some kind of United States of
Europe.
   She says that a proposal to harmonize welfare levels would mean
Britain and West Germany, the two big net contributors to the
community budget, would subsidize the poorest members: Spain,
Greece, Portugal and Ireland.
   On closer monetary cooperation, Mrs. Thatcher is showing some
signs of flexibility. She does not rule out Britain joining the
exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System, which links
the main European currencies.
   But she opposes a central European banking system and the common
currency.
   The labor and economic proposals would need unanimous approval at
a special EEC conference. But Britain cannot stop the other member
countries from at least calling such a conference or giving broad
approval to the social charter.
   Even at home, Euro-bashing no long appears to be a vote-getter
for Mrs. Thatcher.
   A Gallup poll in mid-May showed that 55 percent of 1,274 Britons
questioned said the EEC is ``a good thing,'' compared with 21
percent in 1980.
   In elections for the European Parliament this month, Labor handed
Mrs. Thatcher her first defeat in a national ballot, overturning the
Conservatives' 45-32 majority of British seats in the Strasbourg
assembly.
   ``The British people may lack enthusiasm for integration, but her
kind of chauvinism is plainly passing out of fashion,'' wrote
columnist Peter Jenkins in The Independent newspaper. ``She heads
for ... Madrid denied a popular mandate for waging further war.''
</TEXT>
