<FIRST>r a AM-ChineseStudents     06-25 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Students,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Rally For Democracy in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Chinese and American students, singing
``We Shall Overcome,'' honored fallen protesters in Beijing at a
memorial service and rally Sunday.
   Emerging from the somber service into bright sunlight, the
students linked hands in a large circle around a memorial to the
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   They then moved forward to touch the abstract sculpture in
symbolic unity with Chinese students who flocked last month to touch
a replica of the Statue of Liberty in Tienanmen Square.
   Students also rallied in Indianapolis, where about 300 people
gathered to show their anger over the June 3-4 government crackdown
on pro-Democracy supporters in their homeland.
   The Chinese government has said 200 or 300 people were killed,
both soldiers and civilians. However, Chinese witnesses and Western
intelligence sources have said the toll could be as high as 3,000,
most of them civilians.
   ``By killing those who are asking for human rights, the
government (of China) has placed itself in a hopeless position,
against all mankind,'' Zhen Gu, 30, a graduate student from
Shanghai, told the Boston assembly.
   ``It is precisely in the hopelessness of the tyranny that lies
the hope for democracy in China,'' he said.
   In poems and readings at Boston University's Marsh Chapel,
students repeatedly compared the democracy movement in China with
the civil rights movement in the United States.
   They also recalled the long suppression and recent electoral
triumph of the Solidarity trade union in Poland as they sought to
cast events in China in an optimistic light.
   After the service, the students took buses to Boston's City Hall
Plaza, where the mood turned from solemnity to anger. The crowd,
estimated by police at over 1,000, chanted slogans, waved placards
and circulated petitions calling for international condemnation of
the Chinese army's bloody attack on student demonstrators.
   In Indianapolis, students from universities throughout Indiana
carried banners and shouted ``Down with killing, down with Deng
Xiaoping'' as they marched around the federal courthouse in
sweltering heat.
   Motorists honked their support and passers-by stopped jogging to
join the three-block march from the Statehouse to the federal
courthouse, where the students heard messages of support from
representatives of Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., and Rep. Frank
McCloskey, D-Ind.
   ``You will be welcomed in our country,'' Lugar spokesman Keith
Luse told the demonstrators. ``You represent the best and the
brightest in your country. China's loss will be our gain.''
</TEXT>
