<HEAD>Three Dead in Air Ambulance Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with pilot's body found, Ms. Fraser's
condition, edit for transition; picks up 8th graf, `Coast Guard ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARBLEHEAD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An air ambulance carrying five people
crashed moments after takeoff from Pelee Island in Lake Erie,
killing three people, a Canadian police official said Sunday.
   Searchers found the body of pilot Frederick Allen Lewis, 36, of
Greenwood, Novia Scotia, who was killed in the crash late Saturday,
said Constable Wayne O'Brien of the Ontario Provincial Police. Two
passengers died in the wreck.
   Search boats rescued a man and a woman shortly after the plane
crashed about 200 yards west of the Canadian island, said O'Brien.
   Margaret Fraser of Pelee Island was being flown to a hospital in
Windsor, Ontario, for treatment of a broken ankle when the
twin-engine Navajo Chieftan owned by Southwest Air Ltd. of Windsor
crashed, O'Brien said.
   Ms. Fraser was pulled from the plane by co-pilot Peter Marshall,
42, of Windsor and the two were picked up by local boaters, said
O'Brien. They were taken to Metro Hospital in Windsor.
   Marshall was treated for minor burns and released. Ms. Fraser was
listed in satisfactory condition at the hospital.
   The other dead were identified as Ms. Fraser's husband, Ken
Fraser, 62, and ambulance attendant Charles Russell Ransom, 28, of
Harrow in southwestern Ontario.
   Coast Guard divers, boats and a helicopter from Detroit and
Marblehead joined with Canadian police and rescuers from the island
in the search during the night, Attaway said. The Coast Guard pulled
out of the search after Ontario police divers took over the
operation Sunday.
   O'Brien said there is no town or village on Pelee Island, whose
population of about 250 increases to about 1,000 in the summer. The
island lies about 13 miles north of Marblehead, across Sandusky Bay
from Sandusky, and 15 miles south of the Canadian mainland.
