<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-RoseInvestigation 4thLd-Writethru a0716 06-25 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rose Investigation, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0716,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Backs Rose, Restrains Giamatti Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to RECAST, move up judge's comments; picks
up 15th graf, `The judge got ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CSA1,2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball legend Pete Rose gained a reprieve
Sunday from a judge who blocked baseball's commissioner from holding
a hearing that could have banned the Cincinnati Reds manager from
the game for gambling.
   Common Pleas Judge Norbert Nadel, deciding Commissioner A.
Bartlett Giamatti has ``pre-judged'' Rose, granted Rose a temporary
restraining order that put Monday's hearing on hold until at least
July 6.
   ``Giamatti could not be impartial,'' the judge said.
   Nadel said no action may be taken against Rose for two weeks. The
judge said he will consider on July 6 a motion for a preliminary
injunction that would put the case on hold while Nadel decides
whether he or Giamatti should decide Rose's fate.
   The judge said he though Rose's career would be irreparably
harmed if Monday's hearing were held. Nadel found that baseball and
the public interest would not be hurt if the hearing were not held
Monday.
   Rose could be suspended for a year if Giamatti determines he bet
on major-league games. He could be banned for life if he is found to
have wagered on Reds' games.
   Rose was not in the packed courtroom for the decision; he was at
nearby Riverfront Stadium for Sunday's game against Los Angeles.
   In a pre-game interview with radio station WLW, Rose said he was
very happy with the ruling.
   ``I think they proved (Giamatti) already made up his mind,'' Rose
said. ``It just wasn't going to be a fair hearing, in my eyes. It
was obvious he believed my accusers.''
   ``I think we got justice,'' said Rose's attorney, Reuven Katz.
   Giamatti, the former president of Yale University, issued a
statement saying: ``I regret the judge's decision. I have absolutely
no prejudgment or prejudice regarding Pete Rose. We will contest
this matter tooth and nail.''
   Louis Hoynes, who presented baseball's case against Rose, said:
``It's an erroneous ruling. It's a problem, a serious mistake.''
   The unprecedented decision came two days after a hearing in which
baseball special investigator John Dowd revealed that he has
evidence that Rose bet on major-league games, including Reds games,
in 1985, 1986 and 1987.
   On Sunday, Nadel, after reading a letter that Giamatti wrote in
behalf of Rose's chief accuser, Ronald Peters, said, ``It appears to
this court that the commissioner has pre-judged Peter Edward Rose.''
   The judge got the case after Rose's lawyers sued June 19,
asserting Rose had been denied a fair investigation by Dowd. They
also said Giamatti had already decided that Rose is guilty, and they
asked that the court _ not Giamatti _ determine whether the manager
bet on baseball.
   The first step in the case was Rose's request to halt his hearing
with Giamatti.
   Over the years, Charles O. Finley, Ted Turner and other team
owners had gone to court to challenge the broad powers given to
baseball's commissioners, but none had succeeded. Nadel admitted
Friday that allowing a court to intervene would be going into
``previously uncharted waters.''
   Joseph Tomain, a University of Cincinnati law professor, said he
believed Nadel went further than necessary in finding in favor of
Rose.
   ``I think he went further than he had to go,'' Tomain said. ``I
understood him to say on his last point that Giamatti was prejudiced
... and that really should have been the issue at the preliminary
hearing'' in two weeks.
   Tomain said Nadel could simply have said there was evidence that
Rose would not have received a fair hearing and issued a restraining
order to allow for a cooling-off period.
   Fans en route to the Reds' game remained solid in their support
for Rose.
   ``I'm glad about what the judge did,'' said Dougie Fresh of
Cincinnati. ``Giamatti has made up his mind, there's no question. I
think they should leave the man alone.''
   He said his opinion of Rose has not changed, despite allegations
that Rose bet on his own team.
   Bo Hussey of Charlotte, N.C., said he was pleased with Nadel's
ruling because ``they haven't proven anything. He's an innocent man
until proven otherwise.''
</TEXT>
