<FIRST>u i AM-HongKong-Vietnam     06-25 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Vietnam,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Official Leaves for Boat People Talks in Hanoi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hong Kong official left for Hanoi Sunday for
talks with Vietnamese officials on the possible forced repatriation
of Vietnamese boat people from this British colony.
   Secretary for Security John Barnes and the British colony's
political adviser, Richard Clift, were to begin two days of
negotiations in Hanoi on Monday.
   Barnes said last week after returning from the Geneva conference
on Indochinese refugees that Hong Kong's aim ``is to get all
Vietnamese out of Hong Kong, both refugees and non-refugees ... by
resettlement, by repatriation, whichever.''
   He said he was encouraged by Vietnam's expressed willingness at
Geneva to hold bilateral talks with any participating countries.
   At the 60-nation Geneva talks, Hong Kong and Britain argued for
forced repatriation but were opposed by the United States and the
Soviet Union. Vietnam has said it will take back only refugees
returning on their own accord.
   So far, only 143 Vietnamese have returned home from Hong Kong.
   More than 44,000 Vietnamese are now in Hong Kong and officials
say most are not refugees from political persecution but illegal
immigrants seeking better economic conditions.
