<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     06-25 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>White Knight May Rescue Prime Computer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he cut his buyout offer for Prime Computer
Inc. at the eleventh hour, takeover specialist Bennett S. LeBow was
driving a hard bargain. Maybe too hard.
   On Friday, J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., the nation's oldest venture
capital firm, rode into battle as a ``white knight'' friendly to
Prime's management in a deal valued at about $1.25 billion.
   Would Whitney have jumped in if LeBow hadn't cut his price?
   ``I don't know,'' said Don E. Ackerman, a general partner in the
New York City firm. ``He dropped his offer at about the same time we
were coming to grips with a decision, so we never had to think about
it.''
   Wall Street professionals had fewer doubts.
   ``By playing cute, LeBow blew it,'' one arbitrager said flatly,
speaking anonymously.
   Whitney announced an agreement with Prime's board of directors to
buy the company for cash and securities.
   The $1.25 billion value placed on the package by Wall Street
analysts was roughly the same price that LeBow had initially offered
last November, but at least $120 million more than the revised offer
he made June 1.
   Peter Rosenthal, a spokesman for MAI Basic Four Inc., the Tustin,
Calif., computer firm that LeBow heads, said Friday that LeBow would
not comment on the Whitney deal.
   Before LeBow cut his $20-per-share offer, Prime had solicited
more than 50 companies, including Whitney, for a higher offer. When
no one came forward in April or May, it appeared MAI Basic had the
deal sewn up.
   Then, LeBow dropped his price to $19.50 in cash for about 75
percent of Prime's shares and a package of bonds and preferred stock
for the remainder. Analysts valued that offer at about $18 a share,
or $1.13 billion, and Prime immediately postponed its annual meeting
from June 14 to July 26 to try again to get a better price.
   Some analysts say LeBow was justified in cutting his price,
because Prime's earnings forecasts had dropped in the first half of
1989 as the computer industry slumped and the costs of the takeover
battle mounted.
   ``The value of the company went down,'' said Barry F. Willman,
who follows Prime for Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co. in New York.
   On Thursday, shortly after Prime indicated it had found a white
knight, LeBow announced that he would raise his price. But as of
Friday evening, he had not said how much more he would offer.
   Boosted by the Whitney announcement and the possibility of a
bidding war, Prime stock shot up $3.12{ to close at $19 a share
Friday on the New York Stock Exchange. MAI's stock dropped 12{ cents
to $6.25.
   The merger would be the largest single investment ever for
Whitney, a private New York firm founded in 1946 by wealthy
industrialist John Hay Whitney.
   Prime, based in suburban Natick, makes minicomputers and is the
second-largest producer of computer aided design and manufacturing
systems, surpassed only by International Business Machines Corp. It
has 11,200 employees and had sales of $1.6 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
