<FIRST>r f AM-Helmsley     06-25 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selection To Begin In Hotel Queen's Tax Evasion Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hotel queen Leona Helmsley is due in federal
court Monday to face charges that she evaded taxes by billing
personal luxuries _ including a marble dance floor for her mansion _
as business expenses.
   She'll face the charges without her 80-year-old billionaire
husband, Harry, who has been found incompetent to stand trial
because of memory and reasoning problems caused by several slight
strokes. Two former aides are also on trial.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 68, and her husband were indicted in April 1988 on
charges that they evaded personal income taxes by allegedly
disguising about $4 million in renovations to their Greenwich,
Conn., mansion.
   Jury selection begins Monday, with opening arguments expected
July 5.
   Joseph Brodsky, lawyer for Helmsley aide Frank Turco, has been
given permission to hand potential jurors a questionnaire asking
their incomes and attitudes toward the wealthy, the New York Post
reported Sunday.
   Brodsky said he wants to know if the potential jurors are
``biased against rich people.''
   ``Or whether they've seen Mrs. Helmsley's ads in the newspapers
and they think she's an ogre,'' he said.
   The couple head a $5 billion real estate and hotel empire.
   Mrs. Helmsley is portrayed in advertisements as the ``Queen of
the Helmsley Hotels.'' The ad campaign calls the luxury Helmsley
Palace in Manhattan, directly behind St. Patrick's Cathedral, ``the
only palace in the world where the queen stands guard.'' But some
disaffected former employees have accused her of being demanding to
the point of being abusive.
   The other defendants, Turco and Joseph V. Licari, are charged
with helping create false invoices to make it appear that the costly
renovations on the $8 million, 28-room mansion were tax-deductible
improvements on business properties.
   Among the renovations cited in the indictment was a marble dance
floor installed above a swimming pool; a breakfast room; an
indoor-outdoor stereo system; more than $370,000 in landscaping; and
an assortment of furniture and paintings.
   The indictment said a $45,000 silver clock in the shape of the
Helmsley Building _ a gift for Harry Helmsley _ was billed to and
paid by their Park Lane Hotel. Four jade art objects worth half a
million dollars were paid for by four hotels as furniture purchases,
the indictment said.
   It's not the first tax case Mrs. Helmsley has been involved in.
   Several years ago there were reports that she failed to pay more
than $38,000 in sales tax for jewelry at Van Cleef &amp; Arpels.
   She was never charged, and was given immunity for her cooperation
with authorities and her testimony in cases against merchants of
expensive luxury items, including jewelry. Stores were accused of
shipping empty boxes to addresses out of state so customers could
take goods with them but avoid paying state and city sales taxes.
   The tax evasion case comes to trial after a lengthy pretrial
period during which defense lawyers filed numerous motions to
overturn the 47-count indictment or remove one or both of the
Helmsleys from the case.
   One bid to throw out the indictment went to the U.S. Supreme
Court, which in April rejected the motion that alleged prosecutorial
misconduct for alleged grand jury leaks to the news media.
   Last fall, the Helmsleys' lawyer, Gerald Feffer, claimed that the
false invoices were used by Turco and Licari ``to enable them to
steal blindly from the Helmsleys. That's crucial to our defense.''
   Earlier this month, U.S. District Judge John Walker found Harry
Helmsley unable to assist in his own defense because of the
stroke-related problems. The ruling did not dismiss the charges
against Helmsley but indefinitely delayed his trial.
   The judge noted that medical experts believed Helmsley's mental
deterioration would continue and said it was unlikely he would be
tried.
</TEXT>
