<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Ritchie     06-25 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Ritchie,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bidder To Lorenzo: Let Expert Decide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago options trader Joseph Ritchie has challenged
Eastern Airlines Chairman Frank Lorenzo to let an independent expert
decide whose rebuilding plan for the strike-hobbled carrier is
better.
   ``I'm willing to put my money where my mouth is, and I
respectfully request Mr. Lorenzo do the same,'' Ritchie said in a
telephone interview over the weekend from his Chicago home.
   Ritchie said his union-backed plan could still save Eastern,
while he considers Lorenzo's rebuilding plan to be ``a disguised
liquidation.''
   ``My plan has an immediate ramp-up with all the workers coming
back motivated,'' Ritchie said Saturday.
   Lorenzo's plan, which calls for the sale of $1.8 billion in
Eastern assets to reduce the airline to about two-thirds its
pre-strike size, goes against industry opinion and even Lorenzo's
own past philosophy because it shrinks instead of enlarges the
airline, Ritchie said.
   Texas Air Corp., Eastern's parent company, rejected Ritchie's bid
for Eastern earlier this month, but the bankruptcy court gave
Ritchie permission to continue pursuing his bid while Lorenzo seeks
approval for his rebuilding plan from Eastern's creditors.
   Ritchie is the latest in a series of would-be Eastern buyers, and
Lorenzo last week called the effort to sell the carrier intact ``a
joke'' promoted by the unions to keep members from crossing picket
lines in the 3{-month-old strike.
   Ritchie said he had been keeping his ongoing efforts private, but
Lorenzo's comments prompted him to challenge the chairman publicly.
   ``If it's a joke, I would be happy to let a neutral third party
set us straight,'' Ritchie said. ``If I didn't believe this can
work, I wouldn't be spending all this time and money.''
   Ritchie said, though, that Lorenzo wouldn't willingly allow an
independent party assess Ritchie's plan.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said Saturday that Ritchie's plan
had already been studied by an independent party: the bankruptcy
court examiner and his analyst.
   ``The Ritchie plan is a colossal joke. Entering into a charade
... by submitting it again to another third party just prolongs the
agony of false hope for the striking unions and their members,''
Matell said. He called Eastern's own plan clearly in the best
interests of all parties involved.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland, who has had jurisdiction
over Eastern since the company filed March 9 for Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization, has declined union requests to appoint a
trustee to take over management of Eastern from Lorenzo.
   The unions took heart last week from a request by U.S. Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., that Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner look
into the Eastern situation, while other House members set an
aviation subcommittee hearing on Eastern for Thursday.
   Ritchie said, though, that Eastern is nearing the point of no
return because of management's steady asset sales. Eastern has
announced nearly $900 million in sales, either approved or pending
approval in court.
   ``By the time the truth comes out, it might be too late,''
Ritchie said. ``If he's allowed to continue selling off assets, he's
going to make it untenable for anybody.''
   Ritchie declined to give details of his bid, but he said Lorenzo
wants a price far in excess of what he believes Eastern is worth and
that would leave Eastern in a nearly impossible cash position.
   Ritchie reportedly has been improving his earlier bid by coming
up with more cash up front. According to the reports, he would offer
about $100 million cash, with substantial union concessions starting
with $250 million in the first six months. Other backing would come
through debt and equity financing.
   ``Our offer is very substantially above what we believe to be the
value of the company,'' Ritchie said.
</TEXT>
