<FIRST>r f AM-UAWConvention     06-25 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW Convention,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Dissidents Put a Spin on Their Convention Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Tucker stood before his troops in a
ballroom at the Jolly Roger Motel, rallying them to keep up their
dissent after a week of losing fights on the United Auto Workers
union convention floor.
   The 300 or so New Directions movement members were licking their
wounds as the week-long convention here wound down. But they said
UAW members should stay tuned _ the dissident group had things
planned.
   ``When we leave Anaheim, we will be intact and growing in the UAW
across the country,'' Tucker said last week.
   The next time New Directions members confront the union's
leadership publicly may not come until next spring, when the union
holds its bargaining convention to set policies for negotiations
with the Big Three automakers in the summer of 1990. The UAW's
contracts with the companies expire Sept. 14, 1990.
   New Directions claims proportionately more members in the
rank-and-file than were among the 2,100 delegates at the triennial
convention.
   ``We've gotten here by coming up through the shop floor,'' Tucker
said, ``They have come down from unreachable Solidarity House (the
UAW headquarters) and have imposed directions on us.''
   Tucker's words came in the aftermath of defeat.
   New Directions lost attempts at the convention to alter the
makeup of more than a dozen of the hundreds of convention
delegations, claiming some delegates won illegal local elections.
There is a chance that the movement will go to the Labor Department
to seek new elections.
   The dissidents suffered their second setback when the convention
turned back an effort to change the method of electing top national
officers. Officers currently are elected by a vote of convention
delegates; New Directions wanted it changed to a unionwide
referendum of rank-and-file members that the group said would
provide more democracy in the union.
   New Directions also attempted to limit the use of
labor-management joint programs in factories, saying it eroded the
traditional role of a union. That failed, too.
   Tucker himself also suffered a big loss. Roy Wyse was elected UAW
director from Region 5, thwarting a re-election bid by Tucker to the
same seat.
   At the time, Wyse said the defeats signaled ``the beginning of
the end for the New Directions movement.''
   Later, Tucker said: ``I think Brother Wyse will soon find that
New Directions is reaching an acceleration that will worry the
administration down the road until these very people are traded in.''
   UAW President Owen Bieber and his Administration Caucus denied
all of New Directions' charges, but acknowledged they made an impact
on the convention.
   ``This group was perhaps better organized that (dissident) groups
of the past,'' Bieber said.
   Just after Tucker lost his re-election bid, Bieber suggested that
some of the New Directions arguments have little substance.
   ``I think a lot of that rhetoric out there was designed to
promote people's political futures,'' the union president said.
   But Tucker and his backers rejected that suggestion, saying their
issues are serious and will be around a long time.
   ``When you look at joint programs, look at the most modern,''
said New Directions member Ed Tweed of Local 5960 in Lake Orion,
Mich. ``At all of these (plants), there's nothing but New
Directions.''
   In each of the New Directions issues that came up on the floor,
the organization had the support of no more than 20 percent of the
delegates.
   Nevertheless, New Directions members were undaunted.
   ``They didn't intimidate us,'' Tweed said. ``We fought for what
we said we would.
   ``We're out here to plant seeds, he added. ``Next time, we're
going to harvest them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
