<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EmissionStandards     06-25 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Emission Standards,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush To Request Relaxed Pollution Standard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush Administration will ask Congress to allow
automakers more flexibility in meeting pollution standards, a
federal official said.
   The president's air pollution control bill will propose
eliminating a requirement that nearly every passenger car meet the
same pollution limits, said Richard Wilson, director of the
Environmental Protection Agency's Office of Mobile Sources.
   Wilson said ``emissions averaging'' would allow automakers to
make low-polluting cars that would offset other vehicles that fail
to meet federal pollution standards.
   The provision will be included in Bush's proposed Clean Air Act,
which will be submitted to Congress within the next two weeks, the
Detroit Free Press reported Saturday.
   Auto industry officials declined to comment on the Bush plan,
which is similar to proposals they have made in the past.
   William Noack, a General Motors Corp. spokesman in Washington,
said the company's policy is not to comment on legislation it has
not reviewed. However, he said ``We favor those systems which allow
for flexibility in market-based incentives,'' when asked for general
comment on emissions averaging.
   Environmentalists oppose any such plan.
   ``We are not enthusiastic about the idea,'' said David Hawkins,
senior attorney for the Natural Resources Defense Council. ``We
don't like the idea of being able to sell dirty cars in one location
in return for a manufacturer being able to sell cleaner cars in
another location.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890625-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Economy     06-25 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Economy,0858</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Needs Foreign Debt Agreement For Economic Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico wants to hold out for the maximum
reduction in its towering foreign debt in talks with banks but at
the same time needs an agreement soon to be able to promote economic
growth and stability.
   For Mexico, what is at stake in the negotiations under way in New
York goes beyond how much the country can save in payments on its
$107.4 billion foreign debt, the second highest in the developing
world after Brazil's.
   If banks balk at what Mexico considers a good agreement, the
government's alternatives are to accept less favorable terms or
suspend payments to try to force more concessions, something
considered a last resort.
   Mexico went into the talks seeking a 55 percent reduction in the
prinicipal it owes commercial banks and has come down to 45 percent,
sources close to the talks say. The committee representing more than
500 creditor banks has offered 22 percent and is moving toward 30
percent.
   ``It's not a matter of being able to pay, it's being able to
grow,'' said Jonathan Heath of MACRO Asesoria Economica, a
consulting firm.
   The government wants to reduce the payments from 7 percent to 2
percent of the gross domestic product.
   During the six years after the end of the oil boom in 1982, the
country averaged virtually no economic growth. Workers' salaries buy
only half as much as they did. Since he took office Dec. 1,
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has emphasized renegotiation of
the foreign debt as an important part, but not the entire solution,
to the economic crisis.
   In a recent interview with executives and members of The
Associated Press, Salinas said negotiations were going more slowly
than he would have liked. He said they were likely to take weeks and
perhaps even months more.
   ``There's not much time because the social demands are there. At
the same time it's a very complicated negotiation,'' he said.
   If Mexico reaches its goals on reduction of principal, fresh
funds and other results of the negotiations, the nation hopes to
save about $7 billion a year on interest and principal payments.
Without an agreement, it would spend an estimated $16 billion this
year.
   More than as a source for financing projects, the government is
counting on the agreement to stimulate the private investment needed
to shake the economy out of stagnation. Its target is 6 percent
growth by 1994.
   To reduce capital flight during the prolonged negotiations, the
government has held interest rates high. Even so, some analysts say,
some money has trickled out.
   When it became apparent that its July target for an agreement
wouldn't be met, an 18-month-old anti-inflation agreement with
labor, the private sector and farmers was renewed early to calm
anxiety. It includes a continuation of the one-peso-a-day
devaluation rate through March 1990.
   A favorable agreement would help protect the currency against
further devaluation, reduce the need for government borrowing and
thereby free up the credit for others, and relieve pressure on
interest rates, cutting expenses for both the government and private
borrowers, economists said.
   With only moderate relief from the banks, there is greater risk
of renewed inflation, devaluation, big deficits and other problems
that would thwart growth, said Abel Beltran-del-Rio, director of
CIEMEX-Wefa, economic consultants in Philadelphia.
   Banks argue that too liberal an agreement would pose serious
financial trouble for some of them.
   Mexico is breaking ground for a line of Third World debtor
countries seeking to renegotiate. Each one is certain to want better
terms.
   Of the estimated $70 billion of Mexico's debt in foreign
commercial banks, $38 billion is being renegotiated in the talks.
   While no one is saying a suspension of payments is imminent, the
government has the political groundwork prepared. Labor, farm and
even some government-aligned business leaders have said they would
support Salinas if a moratorium is needed.
   Some private economists also support a strong stand.
   ``A rapid, bad solution worries me more than a solution that
takes longer but that is solid,'' said Manuel Sanchez, director of
the Center for Economic Analysis and Research, a private think tank.
   ``The country cannot continue making sacrifices and the advances
in the stability program cannot be interrupted.''
   If it suspends payments, the government would be able to use the
money it spends on debt service. But the savings could be exceeded
by a spree of dollar-buying by investors.
   Mexico has been considered an exemplary debtor. It's kept up with
service payments and, in addition to the anti-inflation program, the
government has begun restructuring the economy, weaning it from
dependence on state-owned companies, subsidies and protectionism.
   Salinas has complied on the political front, attacking the
corruption and drug trafficking so strongly criticized in the United
States. The Bush administration has responded as Mexico hoped, by
pressuring the banks to give Mexico more economic relief, sources
close to the talks say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890625-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-89 1910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CoalStrike     06-25 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildcat Strikes Enter Third Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT HARVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildcat coal strikes around the nation
that have left some tempers flaring cooled over the weekend, and
police are hoping they stay that way.
   ``Everybody's pretty tired,'' said state police Sgt. C.R.
Smithers of the Beckley detachment, based in the heart of coal
country. ``We've all been working pretty hard to keep up with this.''
   The strikes, which enter their third week Monday, began in West
Virginia on June 12 as union miners walked off the job to express
sympathy with other United Mine Workers members striking Pittston
Coal Group Inc. As of Sunday, about 43,000 miners in nine states
remained off the job.
   In addition to West Virginia, wildcat strikes are being staged in
Illinois, Pennsylvania, Alabama, Ohio, Indiana, Kentucky, Virginia
and Tennessee.
   About 350 strikers in Missouri announced they would return to
work Monday.
   On Sunday, officials at Citizens Gas and Coke Utility in
Indianapolis said they will respond to the strike by cutting coke
production by about one third, beginning Monday.
   Spokesman Steve Scott said Indianapolis-area foundaries will be
affected, but said the cutbacks will not affect the company's
220,000 residential gas customers.
   Scott said the cutbacks will extend the utility's reserves from
one month to about 50 days. Citizens Gas' primary coal supply comes
from West Virginia; other Indiana utlities have reported adequate
coal reserves.
   The UMW has offered no explanation for the wildcat walkouts,
which coal producers say violate the union's national contract, and
it doesn't officially recognize them. But miners who walked off the
job in Appalachia and the Midwest say they're striking in sympathy
with the Pittston strikers.
   That strike, which began April 5 in Virginia and West Virginia
and spread to Kentucky on June 19, has idled 1,900 workers. The UMW
struck Pittston when contract negotiations stalled over wage and
benefit disputes; the miners had worked for 14 months without a
contract.
   Several coal companies have gone to court in at least three
states in an effort to force the miners back to work. Lester Weist,
spokesman for UMW Local 5179 in Oakland City, Ind., said Sunday
those legal efforts could end up prolonging the strike in Indiana,
where all 1,750 union miners have been out since June 16.
   ``If there is anything they can do to strengthen the resolve of
the strikers, that's it,'' Weist said.
   Another UMW official in Indiana, however, said he hopes the
miners will be back on the job later this week.
   ``We've encouraged them to return to work daily, so we'll just
have to wait and see,'' said Roger Myers, an executive board member
for UMW District 11.
   Scattered incidents of violence have been reported during the
strikes. In Alabama and West Virginia, shootings were reported last
week, with a West Virginia teen-ager grazed by a bullet. However,
police reported relative calm throughout the coal fields this
weekend.
   Smithers said authorities have been trying to prevent incidents
such as the one in which Jamie Blankenship, 19, suffered a minor
head wound Thursday at a non-union mine in the southern West
Virginia coal fields. Authorities say they don't know who fired the
shot.
   But the trooper said it's hard to prevent such violence in a
region where strikes often have turned bloody.
   ``It can certainly get a lot worse,'' Smithers said.
   The end of the walkouts apparently hinges on the outcome of the
UMW's negotiations with Pittston, and the company and the union
currently aren't at the bargaining table.
   Federal mediators were called in earlier, but the union dropped
out of those negotiations June 7, and Pittston later declared an
impasse and implemented its own contract.
   UMW President Richard Trumka this weekend blasted Pittston for
the failure in negotiations.
   ``The Pittston Coal Co., over a 17-month period, has been
absolutely intransigent,'' he said. ``They've rebuffed every offer.''
   Company officials have called the union's demands unrealistic.
